# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boules
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Acrobatic gymnasts perform in one of five units: pairs (same-gender or mixed) or same-gender groups (three for women, four for men).
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] In each partnership, the gymnasts' different sizes and abilities will be balanced to complement each other in order to carry out the complex moves.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Some will mainly carry out supporting and pitching roles and are known as bases.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] They are then balanced with usually smaller gymnasts who become the 'tops'.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] In men's and women's groups there are also one or two 'middles', who are like another base who usually will support the top while balancing on the base.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] In competition, partnerships perform a routine to music, which has usually been choreographed specifically for them.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The gymnasts carry out their acrobatic moves and combine them with dance, all in time to and in keeping with the style of the music.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Partnerships are judged on artistry/dance, execution of skills, and difficulty of skills, with the scoring emphasis on execution.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The rules for the sport, known as the Code of Points, are governed by the FIG.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] These rules are subject to change every four years in line with the Olympic cycle, as in other disciplines of gymnastics.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Acrobatics have a long history dating back thousands of years across the world and appeared in festivals, early circuses, and later vaudeville acts as a form of entertainment.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The first use of acrobatics as a specific sport was in the Soviet Union in the 1930s, though its development was interrupted by the World War II.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The first competition, for men only, was held in 1939, with a women's event being added the next year.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] In 1957, the first international competition was held between the Soviet Union, Poland, Bulgaria, and East Germany.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The International Federation of Sports Acrobatics was established in 1973, and the first world championships were held in 1974.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The federation dissolved in 1998, and acrobatic gymnastics was from then on governed by the FIG.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] It was originally called **sports acrobatics** but has been known as **acrobatic gymnastics** since 2007.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] In addition to the current five categories, two additional categories for tumbling (men's and women's) were included until the 1999 World Championships, though some groups still involve tumbling events.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] In the United States, the first national sports acrobatics organization was called the United States Sports Acrobatics Federation (USSAF).
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Founded in 1975, its name was changed to the United States Sports Acrobatics (USSA) in the 1990s.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The USSA then merged with USA Gymnastics in 2002, and acrobatic gymnastics is now a discipline therein.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] For example, the 28th Acrobatic Gymnastics European Championships were held in Rzeszów, Poland, in October 2017.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] There are also numerous national, state, and regional competitions that are held in each country.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Local and regional competitions often form the qualification stages required to compete at national championships.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] There is no requirement from the FIG for gymnasts to have qualified through their own national championships to compete internationally, but local governing bodies will often make their national team selections based on performance at national competition.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] At the London 2012 Olympics, acrobatic partnerships were seen performing before the Olympic gymnastics' events, and during the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gold, silver, and bronze medals are generally awarded in the usual fashion, although in some competitions, a minimum score is required to qualify for medals.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasts may only participate in one level and unit (pair or group) at a competition.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The number of required routines at a competition depends on the level at which the gymnasts are competing.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] At the junior and senior levels, all three routines mentioned below are required.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] At lower age levels, only a single simpler routine is required.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Each of the routine types has a different emphasis, but all include tumbling and dance as elements.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Dynamic (formerly known as Tempo) – These routines demonstrate power, strength and grace through the performance of acrobatic moves that involve the phases of spring, flight, rotation, and landing.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] This often involves the base, or bases in the partnership propelling the top through the air and through a series of somersaults or twists.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The top is generally caught or supported in the landing by their base(s).
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Dynamic routines last approximately two minutes.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Combined – At the more senior levels of competition (11–19 through senior levels), a third routine must be performed that combines both balance and dynamic moves, along with the usual tumbling and dance (tumbling is not required from senior level athletes).
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Typically, it is performed as a final's routine, with a duration, depending upon the level of competition, of approximately 2 minutes and 30 seconds.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] As in artistic gymnastics, compulsory routines, consisting of a prescribed sequence of elements, were previously required along with optional routines, consisting of elements chosen by the gymnasts and their coaches, although this is no longer the case at the highest level of the sport.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The final score of a routine is the sum of the **difficulty**, **execution**, and **artistry** scores, minus any additional penalties incurred.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] For seniors, the difficulty score is open-ended with no maximum, while the execution and artistry scores have a starting value of 10 points and are lowered for specific mistakes made by the gymnasts.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Emphasis is put on the execution score, which is doubled to provide the final score.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Difficulty is the sum of the difficulty value assigned to each element the gymnasts perform during an exercise.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Senior gymnasts have no difficulty limit.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasts submit a 'tariff sheet' listing their planned elements ahead of the competition.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Execution is the degree to which the gymnasts performs an element with aesthetic and technical perfection.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Execution penalties are subtracted from the starting score of 10 and concern aspects such as the amplitude of flight elements, correctness of body shapes, and controlled landings.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Penalties range from 0.1 for small mistakes, such as a small bend at the waist in a handstand, to 0.5 for large ones.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] A top falling rather than being caught by a partner is a one-point deduction.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Artistry evaluates the relationship of the gymnasts with each other and the music, the choreography of the routine, and the variety displayed in a routine.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The choreography of the routine use the whole floor and flow logically from one element to the next, gymnasts should display emotion throughout the performance and perform well with each other, and the choreography should show creativity and original elements.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Penalties are deducted from the final score.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] In 1978, each element was evaluated as either a Group 1 element or Group 2 element, with Group 1 elements being worth 0.4 difficulty points and Group 2 elements being worth 0.2.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] A routine required at least five elements, at least three of which were required to be Group 2 elements.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The minimum difficulty level started a routine at 9.0 points, with the maximum being 10.0.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] For the 2025–2028 code, changes were made to encourage variety and allow for mixed series of balance and dynamic elements while keeping the code relatively stable for the benefit of countries where acrobatic gymnastics is still developing.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] The judging panels of acrobatic gymnastics are similar to other disciplines of gymnastics where different panels of judges are overseen by a head judge, and each panel has a 'Chair of the Judging Panel' (CJP) who oversees that panel's activities.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasts train new elements with plenty of safety mats as well as safety harnesses, which are also called spotting belts.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasiums must have a high ceiling to make sure gymnasts at the top of pyramids or being thrown high in the air do not hit the ceiling.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] To support a grip on the head, bases will often keep their hair short or shave the area gripped by a top, and they may use chalk to assist the top's grip.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Most acrobatic gymnastics injuries occur in the lower limbs, such as to the knee and ankle, with wrist injuries also being relatively frequent.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Ligament injuries are common, though one study found a sex difference, with female gymnasts most frequently having ligament injuries while male gymnasts were most likely to have tendon injuries.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] Bases are more frequently injured than tops, and tops are more prone to acute injuries such as fractures or sprains, while bases are more prone to overuse injuries.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] As in other gymnastics disciplines, disordered eating is a concern, although it is not well-studied in acrobatic gymnastics in particular.
[src:boules/acrobatic-gymnastics] One study surveyed female gymnasts aged 10–19 participating in a World Cup event for indicators of disordered eating; they found that older gymnasts, gymnasts acting as bases, and gymnasts from Eastern Europe were at higher risk of disordered eating behaviors.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] The performance area is a floor 10 metres (33 ft) square.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Trio, groups, and aerobic dance and step groups may consist of gymnasts of any combination of genders.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Gymnasts frequently compete in more than one competition category at the same competition and are allowed to compete in up to three at the World Championships.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] All routines last for 1 minute and 20 to 30 seconds.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Women must wear a leotard with tights or a full-length unitard, and men must wear either a form-fitting top with shorts or pants or a full-length unitard.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Men are not permitted to have sequins or long sleeves on their competition costume.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] For individual, pairs, trio, and group routines, scores have three components: **difficulty**, **execution**, and **artistry**, which are added together to create the final score.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] For dance and step routines, scores only consist of artistry and execution scores.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Individual routines consist of eight elements; performing more elements incurs a deduction.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Elements include dynamic strength elements such as pushup variations and leg circles, static strength elements like planches that may be performed while turning on the hands, jumps, turns, and splits.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Limited acrobatic elements such as handsprings are allowed as well.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Up to three elements may be performed in combination with each other for a connection bonus.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Gymnasts must perform a variety of elements during their routines.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Individual men must perform a dynamic leap element and may not perform flexibility or balance elements, while individual women must perform a turn.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Pairs, trios, and groups must perform the same elements simultaneously and show multiple instances of two or more people working together in a collaborative movement.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] The **difficulty score** is calculated by adding together the difficulty values of the performed elements, then dividing by a different divisor depending on the competition category, and for trios and groups, gender makeup.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] For example, the difficulty a group routine performed by five men will be divided by 2, that of a mixed-gender group by 1.9, and that of an all-women group by 1.8.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] The **execution score** begins at 10 points, and deductions are taken for wrong technique or mistakes.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] For pairs, trios, and groups, the worst performance of an element across all gymnasts is used to take deductions.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] The **artistry score** has a maximum of 10 points.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Routines are evaluated a variety of criteria, such as creativity, musicality and music composition, quality of aerobic movement patterns, use of space, and performance quality.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Aerobic gymnastics stems from the aerobics trend of the 1980s, which spawned competitions.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] The first national aerobic championships were held in the United States in 1984, organized by Howard and Karen Schwartz, who took aerobics from a fitness activity and developed it into a competitive discipline.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] They also organized the first (pre-FIG) World championships in 1990, with 16 participating countries, and the first World Youth Aerobic Championship in 1998, with specific divisions for athletes aged between 8 and 17 years.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] In 1993, various national federations approached the FIG to request it be included as a gymnastics discipline.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] A Code of Points was developed; the first edition was only 20 pages.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] In 1995, the FIG recognised sport aerobics as a new competitive gymnastics discipline, organised judges and coaches courses and launched the first Aerobic Gymnastics World Championships in Paris, with 34 countries sending competitors.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] In 1997, the IWGA (International World Games Association) included Aerobic Gymnastics in the 5th World Games (Lahti, Finland).
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Since 1999, the European Union of Gymnastics has been conducting Aerobic European Gymnastics Championships in every odd year.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] By 2015, 75 national federations participated in aerobic gymnastics.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] As in other gymnastics disciplines such as rhythmic gymnastics, athletes may feel pressured to be thin, especially for athletes with a higher body mass index, even if they are quite thin by typical standards.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] Pressure to lose weight can come from parents, coaches, peers, and other gymnastics authority figures such as judges, and it can lead to disordered eating behaviors.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] A study of athletes competing at the 2022 World Championships found that those who participated in the study trained an average of 16 to 18 hours a week.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] 73% of participants reported an injury occurring in the previous year.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] The most common injuries were muscle strains, tears, and ruptures as well as sprains.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] The legs, especially the ankle, knee, and foot, were the most commonly injured areas, followed by the shoulders, wrists, and hands in the upper body, followed by the hip and spine.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] More than half of the participants also reported significant stress.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] In the American sketch comedy television series Key & Peele, the duo parodies the '80s video footage of the National Aerobic Championship in a sketch showing one of the aerobic dancers experiencing a meltdown while dancing to the championship theme song.
[src:boules/aerobic-gymnastics] In the Mannrobics taunt in the video game Team Fortress 2, the Alternate-Fire action resembles some moves done in the 1988 Crystal Light National Aerobic Championship.
[src:boules/aikido] It was originally developed by Morihei Ueshiba, as a synthesis of his martial studies, philosophy and religious beliefs.
[src:boules/aikido] Ueshiba's goal was to create an art which practitioners could use to defend themselves against attacks, while also protecting the attackers from injury.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido is often translated as "the way of unifying (with) life energy" or as "the way of harmonious spirit".
[src:boules/aikido] According to the founder's philosophy, the primary goal in the practice of aikido is to overcome oneself instead of cultivating violence or aggressiveness.
[src:boules/aikido] Morihei Ueshiba used the phrase *"masakatsu agatsu katsuhayabi"* (正勝吾勝勝速日, "true victory, final victory over oneself, here and now") to refer to this principle.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido's fundamental principles include: *irimi* (entering), *atemi* (strikes), *kokyu-ho* (breathing control), *sankaku-ho* (triangular principle), and *tenkan* (turning) movements which redirect the opponent's attack momentum.
[src:boules/aikido] Its curriculum comprises various techniques, primarily throws and joint locks.
[src:boules/aikido] It includes a weapons system encompassing the *bokken*, *tantō*, and *jō*.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido derives mainly from the martial art of Daitō-ryū Aiki-jūjutsu, but began to diverge from it in the late 1920s, partly due to Ueshiba's involvement with the Ōmoto-kyō religion.
[src:boules/aikido] Ueshiba's early students' documents bear the term *aiki-jūjutsu*.
[src:boules/aikido] Ueshiba's senior students have different approaches to aikido, depending partly on when they studied with him.
[src:boules/aikido] Today, aikido is found all over the world in a number of styles, with broad ranges of interpretation and emphasis.
[src:boules/aikido] However they all share techniques formulated by Ueshiba and most have concern for the well-being of the attacker.
[src:boules/aikido] The term *aiki* does not readily appear in the Japanese language outside the scope of budō.
[src:boules/aikido] This has led to many possible interpretations of the word. 合 (*Ai*) is mainly used in compounds to mean 'combine, unite, join, meet', examples being 合同 (combined/united), 合成 (composition), 結合 (unite/combine/join), 連合 (union/alliance/association), 統合 (combine/unify), and 合意 (mutual agreement).
[src:boules/aikido] There is an idea of reciprocity, 知り合う (to get to know one another), 話し合い (talk/discussion/negotiation), and 待ち合わせる (meet by appointment).
[src:boules/aikido] The term *dō* in Aikido is found in many other Japanese martial arts such as, judo and kendo, and in various non-martial arts, such as Japanese calligraphy (*shodō*), flower arranging (*kadō*) and tea ceremony (*chadō* or *sadō*).
[src:boules/aikido] Therefore, from a purely literal interpretation, aikido is the "Way of combining forces" or "Way of unifying energy", in which the term *aiki* refers to the martial arts principle or tactic of blending with an attacker's movements for the purpose of controlling their actions with minimal effort.
[src:boules/aikido] One applies *aiki* by understanding the rhythm and intent of the attacker to find the optimal position and timing to apply a counter-technique.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido was created by Morihei Ueshiba (植芝 盛平) (1883–1969), referred to by some aikido practitioners as *Ōsensei* (*Great Teacher*).
[src:boules/aikido] The term *aikido* was coined in the 20th century.
[src:boules/aikido] Ueshiba envisioned aikido not only as the synthesis of his martial training, but as an expression of his personal philosophy of universal peace and reconciliation.
[src:boules/aikido] During Ueshiba's lifetime and continuing today, aikido has evolved from the *aiki* that Ueshiba studied into a variety of expressions by martial artists throughout the world.
[src:boules/aikido] Ueshiba developed aikido primarily during the late 1920s through the 1930s through the synthesis of the older martial arts that he had studied.
[src:boules/aikido] The core martial art from which aikido derives is Daitō-ryū Aiki-jūjutsu, which Ueshiba studied directly with Takeda Sōkaku, the reviver of that art.
[src:boules/aikido] Additionally, Ueshiba is known to have studied Tenjin Shin'yō-ryū with Tozawa Tokusaburō in Tokyo in 1901, Gotōha Yagyū Shingan-ryū under Nakai Masakatsu in Sakai from 1903 to 1908, and judo with Kiyoichi Takagi (高木 喜代市) (1894–1972) in Tanabe in 1911.
[src:boules/aikido] The art of *Daitō-ryū* is the primary technical influence on aikido.
[src:boules/aikido] Along with empty-handed throwing and joint-locking techniques, Ueshiba incorporated training movements with weapons, such as those for the spear (*yari*), short staff (*jō*), and possibly the bayonet (銃剣, *jūken*).
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido also derives much of its technical structure from the art of swordsmanship (*kenjutsu*).
[src:boules/aikido] Ueshiba moved to Hokkaido in 1912, and began studying under Takeda Sokaku in 1915; His official association with Daitō-ryū continued until 1937.
[src:boules/aikido] However, during the latter part of that period, Ueshiba had already begun to distance himself from Takeda and the *Daitō-ryū*.
[src:boules/aikido] At that time Ueshiba referred to his martial art as "**Aiki Budō**".
[src:boules/aikido] It is unclear exactly when Ueshiba began using the name "aikido", but it became the official name of the art in 1942 when the Greater Japan Martial Virtue Society (*Dai Nippon Butoku Kai*) was engaged in a government sponsored reorganization and centralization of Japanese martial arts.
[src:boules/aikido] After Ueshiba left Hokkaido in 1919, he met and was profoundly influenced by Onisaburo Deguchi, the spiritual leader of the Ōmoto-kyō religion (a neo-Shinto movement) in Ayabe.
[src:boules/aikido] One of the primary features of Ōmoto-kyō is its emphasis on the attainment of utopia during one's life.
[src:boules/aikido] The idea was a great influence on Ueshiba's martial arts philosophy of extending love and compassion especially to those who seek to harm others.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido demonstrates this philosophy in its emphasis on mastering martial arts so that one may receive an attack and harmlessly redirect it.
[src:boules/aikido] In an ideal resolution, not only is the receiver unharmed, but so is the attacker.
[src:boules/aikido] In addition to the effect on his spiritual growth, the connection with Deguchi gave Ueshiba entry to elite political and military circles as a martial artist.
[src:boules/aikido] As a result of the exposure, he was able to attract not only financial backing but also gifted students.
[src:boules/aikido] Several of the students went on to begin their own styles of aikido.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido was first introduced to the rest of the world in 1951 by Minoru Mochizuki with a visit to France, where he demonstrated aikido techniques to judo students.
[src:boules/aikido] He was followed by Tadashi Abe in 1952, who came as the official Aikikai Hombu representative, remaining in France for seven years.
[src:boules/aikido] Kenji Tomiki toured with a delegation of various martial arts through 15 continental states of the United States in 1953.
[src:boules/aikido] Later in the same year, Koichi Tohei was sent by Aikikai Hombu to Hawaii for a full year, where he set up several dōjō.
[src:boules/aikido] The trip was followed by several visits and is considered the formal introduction of aikido to the United States.
[src:boules/aikido] The United Kingdom followed in 1955; Italy in 1964 by Hiroshi Tada; and Germany in 1965 by Katsuaki Asai.
[src:boules/aikido] Designated the "Official Delegate for Europe and Africa" by Morihei Ueshiba, Masamichi Noro arrived in France in September 1961.
[src:boules/aikido] Seiichi Sugano was appointed to introduce aikido to Australia in 1965.
[src:boules/aikido] Today there are aikido dōjō throughout the world.
[src:boules/aikido] Steven Seagal's film debut *Above the Law* (1988) is regarded as the first American film to feature aikido in fight sequences.
[src:boules/aikido] The largest aikido organization is the Aikikai Foundation, which remains under the control of the Ueshiba family.
[src:boules/aikido] However, aikido has developed into many styles, most of which were formed by Morihei Ueshiba's major students.
[src:boules/aikido] The earliest independent styles to emerge were Yoseikan Aikido, begun by Minoru Mochizuki in 1931, Yoshinkan Aikido, founded by Gozo Shioda in 1955, and Shodokan Aikido, founded by Kenji Tomiki in 1967.
[src:boules/aikido] The emergence of these styles pre-dated Ueshiba's death and did not cause any major upheavals when they were formalized.
[src:boules/aikido] Shodokan Aikido, however, was controversial, since it introduced a unique rule-based competition that some felt was contrary to the spirit of aikido.
[src:boules/aikido] After Ueshiba's death in 1969, two more major styles emerged.
[src:boules/aikido] Significant controversy arose with the departure of the Aikikai Hombu Dojo's chief instructor Koichi Tohei, in 1974.
[src:boules/aikido] Tohei left as a result of a disagreement with the son of the founder, Kisshomaru Ueshiba, who at that time headed the Aikikai Foundation.
[src:boules/aikido] The disagreement was over the proper role of *ki* development in regular aikido training.
[src:boules/aikido] After Tohei left, he formed his own style, called Shin Shin Toitsu Aikido, and the organization that governs it, the Ki Society (*Ki no Kenkyūkai*).
[src:boules/aikido] A final major style evolved from Ueshiba's retirement in Iwama, Ibaraki and the teaching methodology of long term student Morihiro Saito.
[src:boules/aikido] It is unofficially referred to as the "Iwama style", and at one point a number of its followers formed a loose network of schools they called Iwama Ryu.
[src:boules/aikido] Although Iwama style practitioners remained part of the Aikikai until Saito's death in 2002, followers of Saito subsequently split into two groups.
[src:boules/aikido] One remained with the Aikikai and the other formed the independent Shinshin Aikishuren Kai in 2004 around Saito's son Hitohiro Saito.
[src:boules/aikido] Today, the major styles of aikido are each run by a separate governing organization, have their own headquarters (本部道場, *honbu dōjō*) in Japan, and are taught throughout the world.
[src:boules/aikido] The study of *ki* is an important component of aikido.
[src:boules/aikido] The term does not specifically refer to either physical or mental training, as it encompasses both.
[src:boules/aikido] The kanji for *ki* was written in its older form as 氣 up until the Japanese governmental writing reforms after World War II, and now is more prevalently seen in its modern form of 気.
[src:boules/aikido] This form has the removal of the eight directions denoting the pre and post natal energies of *genki* (元氣) (Chinese – *yuán qì*) also known in the Art of Aikido as "Source energy".
[src:boules/aikido] The character for *ki* is used in everyday Japanese terms, such as "health" (元気, *genki*), or "shyness" (内気, *uchiki*).
[src:boules/aikido] *Ki* has many meanings, including "ambience", "mind", "mood", or "intention and action", although its literal meaning is 'air' or 'breath'.
[src:boules/aikido] However, in traditional martial arts and medicine it is often referred to in its more general terminology as "life energy".
[src:boules/aikido] Gozo Shioda's Yoshinkan Aikido, considered one of the "hard styles", largely follows Ueshiba's teachings from before World War II, and surmises that the secret to *ki* lies in timing and the application of the whole body's strength to a single point.
[src:boules/aikido] In later years, Ueshiba's application of *ki* in aikido took on a softer, more gentle feel.
[src:boules/aikido] The concept was known as Takemusu Aiki, and many of his later students teach about *ki* from this perspective.
[src:boules/aikido] Koichi Tohei's Ki Society centers almost exclusively around the study of the empirical (albeit subjective) experience of *ki*, with students' proficiency in aikido techniques and *ki* development ranked separately.
[src:boules/aikido] In aikido, as in virtually all Japanese martial arts, there are both physical and mental aspects of training.
[src:boules/aikido] The physical training in aikido is diverse, covering both general physical fitness and conditioning, as well as specific techniques.
[src:boules/aikido] Because a substantial portion of any aikido curriculum consists of throws, beginners learn how to safely fall or roll.
[src:boules/aikido] The specific techniques for attack include both strikes and grabs; the techniques for defense consist of throws and pins.
[src:boules/aikido] After basic techniques are learned, students study freestyle defense against multiple opponents, and techniques with weapons.
[src:boules/aikido] In some dojo, Uchi-deshi programs permit students to live in the dojo and immerse themselves in practice several times each day.
[src:boules/aikido] Physical training goals pursued in conjunction with aikido include controlled relaxation, correct movement of joints such as hips and shoulders, flexibility, and endurance, with less emphasis on strength training.
[src:boules/aikido] In aikido, pushing or extending movements are much more common than pulling or contracting movements.
[src:boules/aikido] This distinction can be applied to general fitness goals for the aikido practitioner.
[src:boules/aikido] In aikido, specific muscles or muscle groups are not isolated and worked to improve tone, mass, or power.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido-related training emphasizes the use of coordinated whole-body movement and balance similar to yoga or pilates.
[src:boules/aikido] For example, many dōjōs begin each class with warm-up exercises (準備体操, *junbi taisō*), which may include stretching and *ukemi* (break falls).
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido training is based primarily on two partners practicing pre-arranged forms (*kata*) rather than freestyle practice.
[src:boules/aikido] Both halves of the technique, that of *uke* and that of *tori*, are considered essential to aikido training.
[src:boules/aikido] Both are studying aikido principles of blending and adaptation.
[src:boules/aikido] *Tori* learns to blend with and control attacking energy, while *uke* learns to become calm and flexible in the disadvantageous, off-balance positions in which *tori* places them.
[src:boules/aikido] This "receiving" of the technique is called *ukemi*.
[src:boules/aikido] *Uke* continuously seeks to regain balance and cover vulnerabilities (e.g., an exposed side), while *tori* uses position and timing to keep *uke* off-balance and vulnerable.
[src:boules/aikido] In more advanced training, *uke* will sometimes apply reversal techniques (返し技, *kaeshi-waza*) to regain balance and pin or throw *tori*.
[src:boules/aikido] *Ukemi* (受身) refers to the act of receiving a technique.
[src:boules/aikido] Good *ukemi* involves attention to the technique, the partner, and the immediate environment—it is considered an active part of the process of learning aikido.
[src:boules/aikido] The method of falling itself is also important, and is a way for the practitioner to receive an aikido technique safely and minimize risk of injury.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido techniques are usually a defense against an attack, so students must learn to deliver various types of attacks to be able to practice aikido with a partner.
[src:boules/aikido] Although attacks are not studied as thoroughly as in striking-based arts, attacks with intent (such as a strong strike or an immobilizing grab) are needed to study correct and effective application of technique.
[src:boules/aikido] Many of the strikes (打ち, *uchi*) of aikido resemble cuts from a sword or other grasped object, which indicate its origins in techniques intended for armed combat.
[src:boules/aikido] Other techniques which explicitly appear to be punches (*tsuki*), are practiced as thrusts with a knife or sword.
[src:boules/aikido] Kicks are generally reserved for upper-level variations; reasons cited include that falls from kicks are especially dangerous, and that kicks (high kicks in particular) were uncommon during the types of combat prevalent in feudal Japan.
[src:boules/aikido] Beginners in particular often practice techniques from grabs, both because they are safer and because it is easier to feel the energy and the direction of the movement of force of a hold than it is for a strike.
[src:boules/aikido] Some grabs are historically derived from being held while trying to draw a weapon, whereupon a technique could then be used to free oneself and immobilize or strike the attacker while they are grabbing the defender.
[src:boules/aikido] Here is a sample of the basic or widely practiced throws and pins.
[src:boules/aikido] Many of the techniques derive from Daitō-ryū Aiki-jūjutsu, but some others were invented by Morihei Ueshiba.
[src:boules/aikido] The precise terminology for some may vary between organisations and styles; the terms presented are the terms used by the Aikikai Foundation.
[src:boules/aikido] Although the names of the first five techniques listed are in succession, they are not universally taught in numeric order.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido makes use of body movement (*tai sabaki* or 体捌き) to blend the movement of *tori* with the movement of *uke*.
[src:boules/aikido] For example, an "entering" (*irimi*) technique consists of movements inward towards *uke*, while a "turning" (転換, *tenkan*) technique uses a pivoting motion.
[src:boules/aikido] Finally, most techniques can be performed while in a seated posture (*seiza*).
[src:boules/aikido] Techniques where both *uke* and *tori* are standing are called *tachi-waza*, techniques where both start off in *seiza* are called *suwari-waza*, and techniques performed with *uke* standing and *tori* sitting are called *hanmi handachi* (半身半立).
[src:boules/aikido] From these few basic techniques, there are numerous of possible implementations.
[src:boules/aikido] For example, *ikkyō* can be applied to an opponent moving forward with a strike (perhaps with an *ura* type of movement to redirect the incoming force), or to an opponent who has already struck and is now moving back to reestablish distance (perhaps an *omote-waza* version).
[src:boules/aikido] Specific aikido *kata* are typically referred to with the formula "attack-technique(-modifier)"; *katate-dori ikkyō*, for example, refers to any *ikkyō* technique executed when *uke* is holding one wrist.
[src:boules/aikido] This could be further specified as *katate-dori ikkyō omote* (referring to any forward-moving *ikkyō* technique from that grab).
[src:boules/aikido] Weapons training in aikido traditionally includes the short staff (*jō*) (these techniques closely resemble the use of the bayonet, or Jūkendō), the wooden sword (*bokken*), and the knife (*tantō*).
[src:boules/aikido] Some schools incorporate firearm-disarming techniques, where either weapon-taking and/or weapon-retention may be taught.
[src:boules/aikido] Some schools, such as the Iwama style of Morihiro Saito, usually spend substantial time practicing with both *bokken* and *jō*, under the names of *aiki-ken*, and *aiki-jō*, respectively.
[src:boules/aikido] The founder developed many of the empty-handed techniques from traditional sword, spear and bayonet movements.
[src:boules/aikido] Consequently, the practice of the weapons arts gives insight into the origin of techniques and movements, and reinforces the concepts of distance, timing, foot movement, presence and connectedness with one's training partner(s).
[src:boules/aikido] One feature of aikido is training to defend against multiple attackers, often called *taninzudori*, or *taninzugake*.
[src:boules/aikido] Freestyle practice with multiple attackers called *randori* (乱取) is a key part of most curricula and is required for the higher-level ranks.
[src:boules/aikido] *Randori* exercises a person's ability to intuitively perform techniques in an unstructured environment.
[src:boules/aikido] Strategic choice of techniques, based on how they reposition the student relative to other attackers, is important in *randori* training.
[src:boules/aikido] For instance, an *ura* technique might be used to neutralise the current attacker while turning to face attackers approaching from behind.
[src:boules/aikido] In Shodokan Aikido, *randori* differs in that it is not performed with multiple persons with defined roles of defender and attacker, but between two people, where both participants attack, defend, and counter at will.
[src:boules/aikido] In this respect it resembles judo *randori*.
[src:boules/aikido] In applying a technique during training, it is the responsibility of *tori* to prevent injury to *uke* by employing a speed and force of application that is appropriate with their partner's proficiency in *ukemi*.
[src:boules/aikido] When injuries (especially to the joints) occur, they are often the result of a *tori* misjudging the ability of *uke* to receive the throw or pin.
[src:boules/aikido] A study of injuries in the martial arts showed that the type of injuries varied considerably from one art to the other.
[src:boules/aikido] Soft tissue injuries are one of the most common types of injuries found within aikido, as well as joint strain and stubbed fingers and toes.
[src:boules/aikido] Several deaths from head-and-neck injuries, caused by aggressive *shihōnage* in a *senpai/kōhai* hazing context, have been reported.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido training is mental as well as physical, emphasizing the ability to relax the mind and body even under the stress of dangerous situations.
[src:boules/aikido] This is necessary to enable the practitioner to perform the 'enter-and-blend' movements that underlie aikido techniques, wherein an attack is met with confidence and directness.
[src:boules/aikido] Morihei Ueshiba once remarked that one "must be willing to receive 99% of an opponent's attack and stare death in the face" in order to execute techniques without hesitation.
[src:boules/aikido] As a martial art concerned not only with fighting proficiency but with the betterment of daily life, this mental aspect is of key importance to aikido practitioners.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido practitioners (commonly called *aikidōka* outside Japan) generally progress by promotion through a series of "grades" (*kyū*), followed by a series of "degrees" (*dan*), pursuant to formal testing procedures.
[src:boules/aikido] Some aikido organizations use belts to distinguish practitioners' grades, often simply white and black belts to distinguish *kyu* and *dan* grades, although some use various belt colors.
[src:boules/aikido] Testing requirements vary, so a particular rank in one organization is not comparable or interchangeable with the rank of another.
[src:boules/aikido] Some dōjōs have an age requirement before students can take the *dan* rank exam.
[src:boules/aikido] The uniform worn for practicing aikido (*aikidōgi*) is similar to the training uniform (*keikogi*) used in most other modern martial arts; simple trousers and a wraparound jacket, usually white.
[src:boules/aikido] Both thick ("judo-style"), and thin ("karate-style") cotton tops are used.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido-specific tops are available with shorter sleeves which reach to just below the elbow.
[src:boules/aikido] Most aikido systems add a pair of wide pleated black or indigo trousers known as *hakama* (used also in Naginatajutsu, kendo, and iaido).
[src:boules/aikido] In many schools, the wearing of *hakama* is reserved for practitioners with *dan* ranks or for instructors, while others allow all practitioners to wear a *hakama* regardless of rank.
[src:boules/aikido] Aikido styles vary in their intention, due to its holistic nature.
[src:boules/aikido] The most common differences noted in aikido, when observed externally, relate to the intensity and realism of training.
[src:boules/aikido] Stanley Pranin has observed that some criticism may stem from weak attacks from *uke*, allowing for a conditioned response from *tori*, resulting in underdevelopment of the skills needed for the safe and effective practice of both partners.
[src:boules/aikido] To counteract that, some styles allow students to become less compliant over time.
[src:boules/aikido] However, in keeping with the core philosophies, such allowance is granted only after having demonstrated proficiency in being able to protect themselves and their training partners.
[src:boules/aikido] Shodokan Aikido addresses the issue by practicing in a competitive format.
[src:boules/aikido] Such adaptations are debated between styles, with some maintaining that there is no need to adjust their methods because either the criticisms are unjustified, or that they are not training for self-defense or combat effectiveness, but spiritual, fitness or other reasons.
[src:boules/aikido] Reasons for the difference and diversity of teachings, intention, and forms of aikido can be traced to the shift in training focus after the end of Ueshiba's seclusion in Iwama from 1942 to the mid-1950s, as he increasingly emphasized the spiritual and philosophical aspects of aikido.
[src:boules/aikido] As a result, strikes to vital points by *tori*, entering (*irimi*) and initiation of techniques by *tori*, the distinction between *omote* (front side) and *ura* (back side) techniques, and the use of weapons, were all de-emphasized or eliminated from practice.
[src:boules/aikido] Conversely, some styles of aikido place less importance on the spiritual practices which were emphasized by Ueshiba.
[src:boules/air-sports] The term "**air sports**" covers a range of aerial activities, including air racing, aerobatics, aeromodelling, hang gliding, human-powered aircraft, parachuting, paragliding, soaring, and skydiving.
[src:boules/air-sports] Many air sports are regulated internationally by the Switzerland-based Fédération Aéronautique Internationale (FAI) and nationally by aero clubs such as the National Aeronautics Association (NAA) and the Royal Aero Club (RAeC).
[src:boules/air-sports] The FAI has separate commissions for each air sport.
[src:boules/air-sports] For example, the commission for ballooning is the Commission Internationale de l'Aérostation (CIA) and Federation of International Dronesoccer Association (FIDA).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] American football evolved in the United States, originating from the sports of soccer and rugby.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between two college teams, Rutgers and Princeton, using rules based on the rules of soccer at the time; by 1875, the sport had adopted rules similar to rugby union.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A set of rule changes drawn up from 1880 onward by Walter Camp, the "Father of American Football", established concepts that would define the sport, among them the snap, the line of scrimmage, eleven-player teams, and the concept of downs.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Later rule changes legalized the forward pass, created the neutral zone, and specified the size and shape of the football.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The modern sport is closely related to Canadian football, which evolved in parallel with and at the same time as the American game; the two sports are considered the primary variants of gridiron football.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] American football is the most popular sport in the United States; the most popular forms of the game are professional and college football, with the other major levels being high school and youth football.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Over a million Americans played college or high school football in 2022, and the National Football League (NFL) has one of the highest average attendance of any professional sports league in the world.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Its championship game, the Super Bowl, ranks among the most-watched club sporting events globally.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Other professional and amateur leagues exist worldwide, but the sport does not have the international popularity of other American sports like baseball or basketball; the sport maintains a growing following in the rest of North America, Europe, Brazil, and Japan.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Flag football, a variant of the sport, will be played at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In the United States, American football is referred to as "football".
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The term "football" was officially established in the rulebook for the 1876 college football season, when the sport first shifted from soccer-style rules to rugby-style rules.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Although it could easily have been called "rugby" at this point, Harvard, one of the primary proponents of the rugby-style game, compromised and did not request the name of the sport be changed to "rugby".
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The terms "gridiron" or "American football" are favored in English-speaking countries where other types of football are popular, such as the United Kingdom, Ireland, New Zealand, and Australia.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] American football evolved from the sports of rugby and soccer.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Rugby, like American football, is a sport in which two competing teams vie for control of a ball, which can be kicked through a set of goalposts or run into the opponent's goal area to score points.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] What is considered to be the first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between Rutgers and Princeton, two college teams.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] They consisted of 25 players per team and used a round ball that could not be picked up or carried.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] It could, however, be kicked or batted with the feet, hands, head, or sides, with the objective being to advance it into the opponent's goal.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Collegiate play continued for several years with games played using the rules of the host school.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Representatives of Yale, Columbia, Princeton and Rutgers met on October 19, 1873, to create a standard set of rules for use by all schools.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Teams were set at 20 players each, and fields of 400 by 250 feet (122 m × 76 m) were specified.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Harvard abstained from the conference, as they favored a rugby-style game that allowed running with the ball.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] An 1875 Harvard–Yale game played under rugby-style rules was observed by two Princeton athletes who were impressed by it.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] They introduced the sport to Princeton, a feat the Professional Football Researchers Association compared to "selling refrigerators to Eskimos".
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Princeton, Harvard, Yale, and Columbia then agreed to intercollegiate play using a form of rugby union rules with a modified scoring system.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] These schools formed the Intercollegiate Football Association, although Yale did not join until 1879.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Yale player Walter Camp, now regarded as the "Father of American Football", secured rule changes in 1880 that reduced the size of each team from 15 to 11 players and instituted the snap to replace the chaotic and inconsistent scrum.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] While the game between Rutgers and Princeton is commonly considered the first American football game, several years prior in 1862, the Oneida Football Club formed as the oldest known football club in the United States.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The team consisted of graduates of Boston's elite preparatory schools and played from 1862 to 1865.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The introduction of the snap resulted in an unexpected consequence.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Before the snap, the strategy had been to punt if a scrum resulted in a bad field position.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] However, a group of Princeton players realized that, as the snap was uncontested, they could now hold the ball indefinitely to prevent their opponent from scoring.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In 1881, in a game between Yale and Princeton, both teams used this strategy to maintain their undefeated records.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Each team held the ball, gaining no ground, for an entire half, resulting in a 0–0 tie.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] This "block game" proved extremely unpopular with both teams' spectators and fans.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A rule change was necessary to prevent this strategy from taking hold, and a reversion to the scrum was considered.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] However, Camp successfully proposed a rule in 1882 that limited each team to three downs, or tackles, to advance the ball 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Failure to advance the ball the required distance within those three downs would result in control of the ball being forfeited to the other team.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] This change effectively made American football a separate sport from rugby, and the resulting five-yard lines added to the field to measure distances made it resemble a gridiron in appearance.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Other major rule changes included a reduction of the field size to 110 by 53+1⁄3 yards (100.6 m × 48.8 m) and the adoption of a scoring system that awarded four points for a touchdown, two for a safety and a goal following a touchdown, and five for a goal from the field.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Additionally, tackling below the waist was legalized, and a static line of scrimmage was instituted.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Despite these new rules, football remained a violent sport.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Dangerous mass-formations like the flying wedge resulted in serious injuries and deaths.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A 1905 peak of 19 fatalities nationwide resulted in a threat by President Theodore Roosevelt to abolish the game unless major changes were made.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In response, 62 colleges and universities met in New York City to discuss rule changes on December 28, 1905.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] These proceedings resulted in the formation of the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States, later renamed the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The legal forward pass was introduced in 1906, although its effect was initially minimal due to the restrictions placed on its use.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The idea of a 40-yard-wider field was opposed by Harvard due to the size of the new Harvard Stadium.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Other rule changes introduced that year included the reduction of playing time from 70 to 60 minutes and an increase of the distance required for a first down from 5 to 10 yards (4.6 to 9.1 m).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] To reduce infighting and dirty play between teams, the neutral zone was created along the width of the football before the snap.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Scoring was also adjusted: points awarded for field goals were reduced to three in 1909 and points for touchdowns were raised to six in 1912.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Also in 1912, the field was shortened to 100 yards (91 m) long, two 10-yard-long (9.1 m) end zones were created, and teams were given four downs instead of three to advance the ball 10 yards (9.1 m).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The roughing the passer penalty was implemented in 1914, and eligible players were first allowed to catch the ball anywhere on the field in 1918.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] On November 12, 1892, Pudge Heffelfinger was paid $500 (equivalent to $17,917 in 2025) to play a game for the Allegheny Athletic Association against the Pittsburgh Athletic Club.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Despite these extra benefits, the game had a strict sense of amateurism at the time, and direct payment to players was frowned upon, if not prohibited outright.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Over time, professional play became increasingly common, and with it came rising salaries and unpredictable player movement, as well as the illegal payment of college players who were still in school.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The National Football League (NFL), a group of professional teams that was originally established in 1920 as the American Professional Football Association, aimed to solve these problems.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] This new league's stated goals included an end to bidding wars over players, prevention of the use of college players, and abolition of the practice of paying players to leave another team.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] By 1922, the NFL had established itself as America's premier professional football league.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The dominant form of football at the time was played at the collegiate level.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The upstart NFL received a boost to its legitimacy in 1925, however, when an NFL team, the Pottsville Maroons, defeated a team of Notre Dame all-stars in an exhibition game.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A greater emphasis on the passing game helped professional football to distinguish itself further from the college game during the late 1930s.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Football, in general, became increasingly popular following the 1958 NFL Championship game between the Baltimore Colts and the New York Giants, still referred to as the "Greatest Game Ever Played".
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The game, a 23–17 overtime victory by the Colts, was seen by millions of television viewers and had a major influence on the popularity of the sport.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] By the mid-1960s, football was the most popular sport in the United States.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In 1972, polling from Gallup, Inc. found that twice as many Americans identified football as their favorite sport (38%) as compared to baseball (19%); the sport has remained the most popular in the United States since.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In 1960, the American Football League (AFL) was created to compete with the NFL.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The AFL began in relative obscurity but eventually thrived, with an initial television contract with the ABC television network.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The AFL's existence forced the conservative NFL to expand to Dallas and Minnesota in an attempt to destroy the new league.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Meanwhile, the AFL introduced many new features to professional football in the United States and actively recruited minority players.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The AFL also signed several star college players who had also been drafted by NFL teams.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Competition for players heated up in 1965, when the AFL New York Jets signed rookie Joe Namath to a then-record $437,000 contract (equivalent to $4.46 million in 2024).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A five-year, $40 million NBC television contract followed, which helped to sustain the young league.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The bidding war for players ended in 1966 when NFL owners approached the AFL regarding a merger, and the two leagues agreed on one that took full effect in 1970.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] This agreement provided for a common draft that would take place each year, and it instituted an annual World Championship game to be played between the champions of each league.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] This championship game, which would come to be known as the Super Bowl, began play at the end of the 1966 season.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Once the merger was completed, it was no longer a championship game between two leagues, instead being competed between the American Football Conference (AFC) and the National Football Conference (NFC).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Prior to the 1956 college football season, NCAA schools were organized into an upper University Division and lower College Division.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In the summer of 1973, the University Division became Division I, but by 1976, there was a desire to further separate the major football programs from those that were less financially successful, while still allowing their other sports to compete at the top level.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In 1978, the NCAA divided Division I football into two subdivisions: NCAA Division I-A (known today as the Football Bowl Subdivision, or FBS) and Division I-AA (known today as the Football Championship Subdivision, or FCS).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The FCS adopted a single-elimination playoff structure to determine its champion, while the FBS retained its tradition of postseason bowl games.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Each bowl game was associated with a particular conference, and earning a spot in a major bowl game was the reward for winning a conference.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] This arrangement was beneficial to both conferences and bowl games, but it generally prevented the top-ranked teams from meeting in a true national championship game.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Because the NCAA itself does not officially sanction a Division I-FBS national champion, FBS national champions prior to 1992 were determined by polls, which frequently led to controversial or "split" national champions.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In 1992, the Bowl Coalition was created to determine the national champion.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] It was replaced in 1995 by the Bowl Alliance, which itself gave way to the Bowl Championship Series (BCS) in 1997.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] All three of these systems consisted of a single national championship game, as well as a set of other major bowl games.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In 2014, the BCS was replaced by the College Football Playoff (CFP), a single-elimination tournament.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In another major change, in 2021, following legal pressure and antitrust lawsuits, the NCAA and its conferences began allowing schools to offer compensation to student athletes for the use of their names, images, and likenesses (NIL).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] NCAA* allowed schools to directly pay players, ending the traditionally amateur nature of college athletics in the United States.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A football game is played between two teams of 11 players each.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Playing with more on the field is punishable by a penalty.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Teams may substitute any number of their players between downs; this "platoon" system has resulted in teams utilizing specialized offensive, defensive and special teams units.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The number of players allowed on an active roster varies by league; the NFL has a 53-man roster, while NCAA Division I allows teams to have up to 105 players on their roster.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Individual players in a football game must be designated with a uniform number between 0 and 99.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] NFL teams are required to number their players by a league-approved numbering system, and any exceptions must be approved by the commissioner.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] NCAA and NFHS teams are "strongly advised" to number their offensive players according to a league-suggested numbering scheme.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Women are eligible to play in high school, college, and professional football, but most football players are men.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] No woman has ever played in the NFL, but women have played in high school and college football games.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In 2018, women and girls comprised 0.5% of players in Pop Warner Little Scholars youth football, 0.2% of players in high school football, and 10.9% of Americans who report playing tackle football.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The role of the offensive unit is to advance the football down the field with the ultimate goal of scoring a touchdown.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The offensive team must line up in a legal formation before they can snap the ball.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] An offensive formation is considered illegal if there are more than four players in the backfield or fewer than five players numbered 50–79 on the offensive line.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Players can line up temporarily in a position whose eligibility is different from what their number permits as long as they report the change immediately to the referee, who then informs the defensive team of the change.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Neither team's players, except the center (C), are allowed to line up in or cross the neutral zone until the ball is snapped.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Interior offensive linemen are not allowed to move until the snap of the ball.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The main backfield positions are the quarterback (QB), running back (RB), and fullback (FB).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The quarterback is the leader of the offense.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Either the quarterback or a coach calls the plays.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Quarterbacks typically inform the rest of the offense of the play in the huddle before the team lines up.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The quarterback lines up behind the center to take the snap and then hands the ball off, throws it, or runs with it.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The primary role of the running back is to carry the ball on running plays.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Fullbacks tend to be larger than halfbacks and function primarily as blockers, but they are sometimes used as runners in short-yardage or goal-line situations.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The offensive line (OL) consists of several players whose primary function is to block members of the defensive line from tackling the ball carrier on running plays or sacking the quarterback on passing plays.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The most important role on the offensive line is the center, who is not just responsible for blocking and snapping the ball, but also for handling line adjustments and pre-snap strategy.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] On either side of the center are the guards (G), while tackles (T) line up outside the guards.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The principal receivers are the wide receivers (WR) and the tight ends (TE).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Wide receivers line up on or near the line of scrimmage, split outside the line.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The main goal of the wide receiver is to catch passes thrown by the quarterback, but they may also function as decoys or as blockers during running plays.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Tight ends line up next to the offensive line and function both as receivers and as blockers.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The role of the defense is to prevent the offense from scoring by tackling the ball carrier or by forcing turnovers.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Turnovers include interceptions (a defender catching a forward pass intended for the offense) and forced fumbles (taking possession of the ball from the ball-carrier).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The defensive line (DL) consists of defensive ends (DE) and defensive tackles (DT).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Defensive ends line up on the ends of the defensive line, while defensive tackles line up on the inside, between the defensive ends.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The primary responsibilities of defensive ends and defensive tackles are to stop running plays on the outside and inside, respectively, to pressure the quarterback on passing plays, and to occupy the line so that the linebackers can break through.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Linebackers line up behind the defensive line but in front of the defensive backfield.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] They are divided into two types: middle linebackers (MLB) and outside linebackers (OLB).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Linebackers tend to serve as the defensive leaders and call the defensive plays, given their vantage point of the offensive backfield.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Their roles include defending the run, pressuring the quarterback, and tackling backs, wide receivers, and tight ends.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The defensive backfield, often called the secondary, consists of cornerbacks (CB) and safeties (S).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Safeties are themselves divided into free safeties (FS) and strong safeties (SS).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Cornerbacks line up outside the defensive formation, typically opposite a receiver to be able to cover them.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Safeties line up between the cornerbacks but farther back in the secondary.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Safeties tend to be viewed as "the last line of defense" and are responsible for stopping deep passing plays as well as breakout running plays.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The special teams unit is responsible for all kicking plays.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The special teams unit of the team in control of the ball tries to execute field goal (FG) attempts, punts, and kickoffs, while the opposing team's unit will aim to block or return them.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Three positions are specific to the field goal and PAT (point after touchdown) unit: the placekicker (K or PK), holder (H), and long snapper (LS).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The long snapper's job is to snap the football to the holder, who will catch and place it on the ground for the kicker.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] There is usually never a holder on kickoffs, because the ball is kicked off a tee; however, a holder may be used in certain situations, such as if wind is preventing the ball from remaining upright on the tee.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The player on the receiving team who catches the ball is known as the kick returner (KR).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The positions specific to punt plays are the punter (P), long snapper, upback, and gunner.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The long snapper snaps the football directly to the punter, who then drops and kicks it before it hits the ground.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Gunners line up split outside the line and race down the field, aiming to tackle the punt returner (PR)—the player who catches the punt.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Upbacks line up a short distance, typically 1-7 yards, behind the line of scrimmage, providing additional protection to the punter.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In football, the winner is the team that has scored more points at the end of the game.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] There are multiple ways to score in a football game.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The touchdown (TD), worth six points, is the most valuable scoring play.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A touchdown is scored when a live ball is advanced into, caught, or recovered in the opposing team's end zone.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The scoring team then attempts a try, more commonly known as the point(s)-after-touchdown (PAT) or conversion, which is a single scoring opportunity.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by a place kick or drop kick through the goal posts, it is worth one point, typically called the extra point.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by what would normally be a touchdown, it is worth two points; this is known as a two-point conversion.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In general, the extra point is almost always successful, while the two-point conversion is a much riskier play with a higher probability of failure; accordingly, extra point attempts are far more common than two-point conversion attempts.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A field goal (FG), worth three points, is scored when the ball is place kicked or drop kicked through the uprights and over the crossbars of the defense's goalposts.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Almost all field goal attempts are done via place kick.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] While drop kicks were common in the early days of the sport, the shape of modern footballs makes it difficult to reliably drop kick the ball.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The last successful scoring play by drop kick in the NFL was accomplished in 2006; prior to that, the last successful drop kick had been made in 1941.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] After a PAT attempt or successful field goal, the scoring team must kick the ball off to the other team.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A safety is scored when the ball carrier is tackled in the carrier's own end zone.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Safeties are worth two points, which are awarded to the defense.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In addition, the team that conceded the safety must kick the ball to the scoring team via a free kick.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Safeties are the least common method of scoring in football.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Football games are played on a rectangular field that measures 120 yards (110 m) long and 53+1⁄3 yards (48.8 m) wide.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Lines marked along the ends and sides of the field are known as the end lines and sidelines.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Goal lines are marked 10 yards (9.1 m) inward from each end line.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Weighted pylons are placed along each sideline, on the inside corner of the intersections with the goal lines and end lines.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] White markings on the field identify the distance from the end zone.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Inbound lines, or hash marks, are short parallel lines that mark off 1-yard (0.91 m) increments.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Yard lines, which can run the width of the field, are marked every 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A one-yard-wide line is placed at each end of the field; this line is marked at the center of the two-yard line in professional play and at the three-yard line in college play.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Numerals that display the distance from the closest goal line in yards are placed on both sides of the field every ten yards.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Goalposts are located at the center of the plane of the two end lines.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The crossbar of these posts is 10 feet (3.0 m) above the ground, with vertical uprights at the end of the crossbar 18 feet 6 inches (5.64 m) apart for professional and collegiate play, and 23 feet 4 inches (7.11 m) apart for high school play.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The uprights extend vertically 35 feet (11 m) on professional fields, a minimum of 10 yards (9.1 m) on college fields, and a minimum of 10 feet (3.0 m) on high school fields.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Goal posts are padded at the base, and orange ribbons are normally placed at the tip of each upright as indicators of wind strength and direction.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The football itself is a prolate spheroid leather ball, similar to the balls used in rugby or Australian rules football.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] At all levels of play, the football is inflated to 12+1⁄2 to 13+1⁄2 psi (86 to 93 kPa), or just under one atmosphere, and weighs 14 to 15 ounces (400 to 430 g); beyond that, the exact dimensions vary slightly.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In professional play the ball has a long axis of 11 to 11+1⁄4 inches (28 to 29 cm), a long circumference of 28 to 28+1⁄2 inches (71 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 21 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In college and high school play the ball has a long axis of 10+7⁄8 to 11+7⁄16 inches (27.6 to 29.1 cm), a long circumference of 27+3⁄4 to 28+1⁄2 inches (70 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 20+3⁄4 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Football games last for a total of 60 minutes in professional and college play and are divided into two halves of 30 minutes and four quarters of 15 minutes.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] High school football games are 48 minutes in length with two halves of 24 minutes and four quarters of 12 minutes.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The two halves are separated by a halftime period, and the first and third quarters are followed by a short break.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Before the game starts, the referee and each team's captain meet at midfield for a coin toss.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The visiting team can call either "heads" or "tails"; the winner of the toss chooses whether to receive or kick off the ball or which goal they wish to defend.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] They can defer their choice until the second half.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Unless the winning team decides to defer, the losing team chooses the option the winning team did not select—to receive, kick, or select a goal to defend to begin the second half.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Most teams choose to receive or defer, because choosing to kick the ball to start the game allows the other team to choose which goal to defend.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Teams switch goals following the first and third quarters.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] If a down is in progress when a quarter ends, play continues until the down is completed.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] If certain fouls are committed during play while time has expired, the quarter may be extended through an untimed down.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Games last longer than their defined length due to play stoppages—the average NFL game lasts slightly over three hours.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Time in a football game is measured by the game clock.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] An operator is responsible for starting, stopping and operating the game clock based on the direction of the appropriate official.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A separate play clock is used to show the amount of time within which the offense must initiate a play.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The play clock is set to 25 seconds after certain administrative stoppages in play and to 40 seconds when play is proceeding without such stoppages.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] If the offense fails to start a play before the play clock reads "00", a delay of game foul is called on the offense.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] There are two main ways the offense can advance the ball: running and passing.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In a typical play, the center passes the ball backwards and between their legs to the quarterback in a process known as the snap.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The quarterback then either hands the ball off to a running back, throws the ball, or runs with it.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The play ends when the player with the ball is tackled or goes out-of-bounds or a pass hits the ground without a player having caught it.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A forward pass can be legally attempted only if the passer is behind the line of scrimmage; only one forward pass can be attempted per down.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] As in rugby, players can also pass the ball backwards at any point during a play.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In the NFL, a down also ends immediately if the runner's helmet comes off.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The offense is given a series of four plays, known as downs.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] If the offense advances ten or more yards in the four downs, they are awarded a new set of four downs.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] If they fail to advance ten yards, possession of the football is turned over to the defense.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] In most situations, if the offense reaches their fourth down they will punt the ball to the other team, which forces them to begin their drive from farther down the field; if they are in field goal range, they might attempt to score a field goal instead.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A group of officials, the chain crew, keeps track of both the downs and the distance measurements.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The spot needed to secure a first down is known as the line to gain.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] On television, a yellow line is electronically superimposed on the field to show the line to gain to the viewing audience.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] There are two categories of kicks in football: scrimmage kicks, which can be executed by the offensive team on any down from behind or on the line of scrimmage, and free kicks.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The free kicks are the kickoff, which starts the first and third quarters and overtime and follows a try attempt or a successful field goal, and the safety kick, which follows a safety.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] On a kickoff, the ball is placed at the 35-yard line of the kicking team in professional and college play and at the 40-yard line in high school play.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The ball may be drop kicked or place kicked.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] If a place kick is chosen, the ball can be placed on the ground or a tee; a holder may be used in either case.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] On a safety kick, the kicking team kicks the ball from their own 20-yard line.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] They can punt, drop kick or place kick the ball, but a tee may not be used in professional play.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Any member of the receiving team may catch or advance the ball.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The ball may be recovered by the kicking team once it has gone at least ten yards and has touched the ground or has been touched by any member of the receiving team.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The three types of scrimmage kicks are place kicks, drop kicks, and punts.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Only place kicks and drop kicks can score points.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The place kick is the standard method used to score points, because the pointy shape of the football makes it difficult to reliably drop kick.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Once the ball has been kicked from a scrimmage kick, it can be advanced by the kicking team only if it is caught or recovered behind the line of scrimmage.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] If it is touched or recovered by the kicking team beyond this line, it becomes dead at the spot where it was touched.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The kicking team is prohibited from interfering with the receiver's opportunity to catch the ball.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The receiving team has the option of signaling for a fair catch, which prohibits the defense from blocking into or tackling the receiver.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The play ends as soon as the ball is caught, and the ball may not be advanced.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Officials are responsible for enforcing game rules and monitoring the clock.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] All officials carry a whistle and wear black-and-white striped shirts and black hats, except for the referee, whose hat is white.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Each carries a weighted yellow flag that is thrown to the ground to signal that a foul has been called.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] An official who spots multiple fouls will throw their hat as a secondary signal.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Women can serve as officials; Sarah Thomas became the NFL's first female official in 2015.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Another set of officials, the chain crew, are responsible for moving the chains.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The chains, consisting of two large sticks with a 10-yard-long chain between them, are used to measure for a first down.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The chain crew stays on the sidelines during the game, but if requested by the officials, they will briefly bring the chains onto the field to measure.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A typical chain crew will have at least three people—two members of the chain crew will hold either of the two sticks, while a third will hold the down marker.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The down marker, a large stick with a dial on it, is flipped after each play to indicate the current down and is typically moved to the approximate spot of the ball.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The chain crew system has been used for over 100 years and is considered an accurate measure of distance, rarely subject to criticism from either side.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Football is a full-contact sport, and injuries are relatively common.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur during training sessions, particularly ones that involve contact between players.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] To try to prevent injuries, players are required to wear a set of equipment.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] At a minimum players must wear a football helmet and a set of shoulder pads, but individual leagues may require additional padding such as thigh pads and guards, knee pads, chest protectors, and mouthguards.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur in the lower extremities, particularly in the knee, but a significant number also affect the upper extremities.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] The most common types of injuries are strains, sprains, bruises, fractures, dislocations, and concussions.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Repeated concussions (and possibly sub-concussive head impacts) can increase a person's risk in later life for CTE (chronic traumatic encephalopathy) and health issues such as dementia, Parkinson's disease, and depression.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Concussions are often caused by helmet-to-helmet or upper-body contact between opposing players, although helmets have prevented more serious injuries such as skull fractures.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] However, a study in the *Orthopaedic Journal of Sports Medicine* found that Heads Up Football was ineffective; the same study noted that more extensive reforms implemented by Pop Warner Little Scholars and its member teams were effective in significantly reducing concussion rates.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] A 2018 study performed by the VA Boston Healthcare System and the Boston University School of Medicine found that tackle football before age 12 was correlated with earlier onset of symptoms of CTE, but not with increased symptom severity.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] More specifically, each year a player played tackle football under age 12 predicted earlier onset of cognitive, behavioral, and mood problems by an average of two and a half years.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] To help mitigate injuries, the NCAA recommends limiting full contact (tackling to the ground) practices, avoiding full contact on consecutive days, and no more than 20 hours of practice per week.
[src:boules/american-football-p01] Players must receive one day off per week.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The National Football League (NFL) and the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) are the most popular football leagues in the United States.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The National Football League was founded in 1920 and has since become the largest and most popular sport in the United States.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The NFL has the highest average attendance of any sporting league in the world, with an average attendance of 66,960 during the 2011 NFL season.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The NFL championship game is called the Super Bowl, and is among the biggest events in club sports worldwide.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] It is played between the champions of the National Football Conference (NFC) and the American Football Conference (AFC), and its winner is awarded the Vince Lombardi Trophy.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] College football is the third-most popular sport in the United States, behind professional football and professional baseball, respectively.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The NCAA, the largest collegiate organization, is divided into three Divisions: Division I, Division II and Division III.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Division I is the highest level of play, while Division III is the lowest; Division I and II programs can offer athletic scholarships to student-athletes, while Division III programs cannot.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Division I football is further divided into two subdivisions: the Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) and the Football Championship Subdivision (FCS).
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The champions of each level of play are determined through playoff systems.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Other national college football organizations include the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA), which comprises around 90 smaller colleges, and the National Junior College Athletic Association (NJCAA), whose membership consists of two-year colleges.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] High school football is the most popular sport in the United States played by boys.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The NFHS is the largest organization for high school football, with member associations in all 50 states as well as the District of Columbia.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] USA Football is the governing body for youth and amateur football, and Pop Warner Little Scholars is the largest organization for youth football.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The most successful league to directly compete with the NFL was the American Football League (AFL), which existed from 1960 to 1969.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The AFL became a significant rival in 1964 before signing a five-year, US$36 million television deal with NBC.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] AFL teams began signing NFL players to contracts, and the league's popularity grew to challenge that of the NFL.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged in the 1970 season, and all the AFL teams joined the NFL.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] An earlier league, the All-America Football Conference (AAFC), was in play from 1946 to 1949.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] After it had dissolved, two AAFC teams, the Cleveland Browns and the San Francisco 49ers, became members of the NFL; another member, the Baltimore Colts joined the league, but folded after just a year in the NFL.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Other attempts to start rival leagues since the AFL merged with the NFL in 1970 have been far less successful, as professional football salaries and the NFL's television contracts began to escalate out of the reach of competitors and the NFL covered more of the larger cities.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The World Football League (WFL) played for two seasons, in 1974 and 1975, but faced such severe monetary issues it could not pay its players.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] In its second and final season the WFL attempted to establish a stable credit rating, but the league disbanded before the season could be completed.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The United States Football League (USFL) operated for three seasons from 1983 to 1985.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Originally not intended as a rival league, the entry of owners who sought marquee talent and to challenge the NFL led to an escalation in salaries and ensuing financial losses.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] A subsequent US$1.5 billion antitrust lawsuit against the NFL was successful in court, but the league was awarded only $1 in damages, which was automatically tripled to $3 under antitrust law.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The original XFL, created in 2001 by WWE co-founder Vince McMahon, lasted for only one season.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Despite television contracts with NBC and UPN, and high expectations, the XFL suffered from low quality of play and poor reception for its use of tawdry professional wrestling gimmicks, which caused initially high ratings and attendance to collapse.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The United Football League (UFL) began in 2009 but folded after suspending its 2012 season after having lost $120 million over just three seasons.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Another spring league, the Alliance of American Football lasted less than one season, unable to keep investors.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] A revived United States Football League began play in 2022 and quickly faced immediate competition from the XFL, which resumed play in 2023.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged following the 2023 season, forming a new United Football League (UFL).
[src:boules/american-football-p02] American football leagues exist throughout the world, but the game has yet to achieve the international success and popularity of baseball and basketball.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] At the international level, Canada, Mexico, and Japan are considered to be second-tier, while Austria, Germany, and France would rank among a third tier.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] These countries rank far below the United States, which is dominant at the international level.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] NFL Europa, the developmental league of the NFL, operated from 1991 to 1992 and then from 1995 to 2007.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] At the time of its closure, NFL Europa had five teams based in Germany and one in the Netherlands.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] In Germany, the German Football League (GFL) has 16 teams and has operated for over 40 seasons, with the league's championship game, the German Bowl, closing out each season.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The league operates in a promotion and relegation structure with German Football League 2 (GFL2), which also has 16 teams.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The United Kingdom also operated several teams within NFL Europe during the League's tenure.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The resulting rise in popularity of the sport brought the NFL back to the country in 2007 where they now hold the NFL International Series in London, currently consisting of four regular season games.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The continuing interest and growth in both the sport and the series has led to the possible formation of a potential NFL franchise in London.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] NFL commissioner Roger Goodell aims to host 16 international games each year, enough for each NFL team to play one international game each year.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom, the British American Football Association National Leagues (BAFANL), an amateur competition, is the top level of American football.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Teams compete across multiple levels in a promotion and relegation structure; the league's championship is the Britbowl.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] University competition is held through the British Universities American Football League (BUAFL), which was formed in 2007.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] In 2008, the league launched a partnership with the NFL, through its partner organization NFL UK.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] From 2007 to 2014, the BUAFL grew from 42 teams and 2,460 participants to 75 teams and over 4,100 people involved.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The standard form of American football is not an Olympic sport, but it was a demonstration sport at the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The International Federation of American Football (IFAF), an international governing body composed of continental federations, received provisional recognition from the International Olympic Committee (IOC) in 2014 and was fully recognized by the IOC in 2015.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] American football federations are present in Africa, the Americas, Asia, Europe, and Oceania; a total of 75 national football federations exist as of 2023.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The IFAF runs tournaments such as the IFAF World Championship, the IFAF Women's World Championship, the IFAF Junior World Championship, and the Flag Football World Championship.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Obstacles towards the goal of becoming an Olympic sport included the predominant participation of men in international play and the short three-week Olympic schedule.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Large team sizes were an additional difficulty, due to the Olympics' set limit of 10,500 athletes and coaches.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] American football also faced an issue with a lack of global visibility.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Nigel Melville, the CEO of USA Rugby, noted that "American football is recognized globally as a sport, but it's not played globally." To solve these concerns, major effort was put into promoting flag football, a modified version of American football, at the international level.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Flag football for men and women will debut as an Olympic sport at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] "Baseball is still called the national pastime, but football is by far the more popular sport in American society", according to ESPN.com's Sean McAdam.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] In a 2014 poll conducted by Harris Interactive, professional football ranked as the most popular sport, and college football ranked third behind only professional football and baseball; 46% of participants ranked some form of the game as their favorite sport.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Professional football has ranked as the most popular sport in the poll since 1985, when it surpassed baseball for the first time.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Professional football is most popular among those who live in the eastern United States and rural areas, while college football is most popular in the southern United States and among people with graduate and post-graduate degrees.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Football is also the most-played sport by high school and college athletes in the United States.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] A 2022 survey from National Football Foundation found that one million high-school athletes played the sport, with another 81,000 college athletes across both the NCAA and the NAIA.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The Super Bowl is the most popular single-day sporting event in the United States, and is among the biggest club sporting events in the world in terms of TV viewership.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The NFL made approximately $12 billion in revenue in 2022.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Super Bowl games account for eight of the top ten most-watched broadcasts in American history; Super Bowl LVII, played on February 12, 2023, was watched by a record 115.1 million Americans, and is second only to the Apollo 11 moon landing (125 million viewers).
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The NFL is the most valuable sports league in the world, with the average team valued at over $8 billion.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] American football also plays a significant role in American culture.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The day on which the Super Bowl is held is considered a *de facto* national holiday, and in parts of the country like Texas, the sport has been compared to a religion.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Football is also linked to other holidays; New Year's Day is traditionally the date for several college football bowl games, including the Rose Bowl.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] However, if New Year's Day is on a Sunday, the bowl games are moved to another date so as not to conflict with the typical NFL Sunday schedule.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Thanksgiving football is another American tradition, hosting many high school, college, and professional games.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Implicit rules such as playing through pain and sacrificing for the better of the team are promoted in football culture.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] In Canada, the game has a significant following.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] According to a 2013 poll, 21% of respondents said they followed the NFL "very closely" or "fairly closely", making it the third-most followed league behind the National Hockey League (NHL) and Canadian Football League (CFL).
[src:boules/american-football-p02] American football also has a long history in Mexico, which was introduced to the sport in 1896.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] It was the second-most popular sport in Mexico in the 1950s, with the game being particularly popular in colleges.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The *Los Angeles Times* notes the NFL claims over 16 million fans in Mexico, which places the country third behind the U.S. and Canada.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] American football is played in Mexico both professionally and as part of the college sports system.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] A professional league, the Liga de Fútbol Americano Profesional (LFA), was founded in 2016.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Japan was introduced to the sport in 1934 by Paul Rusch, a teacher and Christian missionary who helped to establish football teams at three universities in Tokyo.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Play was halted during World War II by order of Emperor Hirohito, but the sport began growing in popularity again after the war.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] As of 2010, there are more than 400 high school football teams in Japan, with over 15,000 participants, and over 100 teams play in the Kantoh Collegiate Football Association (KCFA).
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The X-League is the largest American football league in Japan, and the largest American football league in the world to use a promotion-relegation system.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Some teams in the X-League, like the Panasonic Impulse, are sponsored by corporations, and all Japanese players on these teams are employed by the corporation.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The league operates in separate spring and fall seasons, with each team playing five games.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The top eight teams make the playoffs, which are played in Tokyo Dome; the champion is determined by the Rice Bowl.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Europe is a major target for the expansion of the game by football organizers.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom in the 1980s, the sport was popular, with the 1986 Super Bowl being watched by over four million people (about 1 out of every 14 Britons).
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Its popularity faded during the 1990s, coinciding with the establishment of the Premier League—the top level of the English association football (soccer) league system.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] According to BBC America, there is a "social stigma" surrounding American football in the UK, with many Brits feeling the sport has no right to call itself "football" due to the lack of emphasis on kicking.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Nonetheless, the sport has retained a following in the United Kingdom; the NFL operates a media network in the country, and since 2007 has hosted the NFL International Series in London.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Super Bowl viewership has also rebounded, with over 4.4 million Britons watching Super Bowl XLVI.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The sport is played in European countries like Switzerland, which has American football clubs in every major city, and Germany, where the sport has around 45,000 registered amateur players.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] It was generally unknown there until the 1980s when a small group of players began playing on Copacabana Beach in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The sport grew gradually with 700 amateur players registering within 20 years.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Games were played on the beach with modified rules and without the traditional football equipment due to its lack of availability in Brazil.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Eventually, a tournament, the Carioca championship, was founded, with the championship Carioca Bowl played to determine a league champion.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The country saw its first full-pad game of football in October 2008.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] According to *The Rio Times*, the sport is one of the fastest-growing sports in Brazil and is almost as commonly played as soccer on the beaches of Copacabana and Botafogo.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Football in Brazil is governed by the Confederação Brasileira de Futebol Americano (CBFA), which had over 5,000 registered players as of November 2013.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The sport's increase in popularity has been attributed to games aired on ESPN, which began airing in Brazil in 1992 with Portuguese commentary.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The popularity and "easy accessibility" of non-contact versions of the sport in Brazil has led to a rise in participation by female players.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] According to ESPN, the American football audience in Brazil increased 800% between 2013 and 2016.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The network, along with Esporte Interativo, airs games there on cable television.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] NFL had expressed interest in having games in the country, eventually resulting in São Paulo's Arena Corinthians hosting Brazil's first NFL game in 2024, and the Super Bowl has become a widely watched event in Brazil at bars and movie theaters.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Further countries have also expressed interest in football to a lesser degree.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The Arab world has expressed growing interest in American football, with many countries in the region being members of IFAF Asia.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Jordan and the United Arab Emirates, which are not members of IFAF, have established their own domestic leagues.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Egypt established two leagues for the sport, namely the Egyptian League of American Football and the Egyptian Federation of American Football, and Saudi Arabia hosts two teams based out of Jeddah and Yanbu respectively.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] China has additionally been a target for the expansion of the sport, with the Mainland being the home of the Chinese National Football League as well as a growing audience of Super Bowl watchers.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Three franchises are also based out of Hong Kong, which prior to the COVID-19 pandemic regularly played mainland teams.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] NFL games average 900,000 viewers in China, though the league has cited logistical challenges which would prevent teams from playing games akin to abroad games in European countries.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Canadian football, the predominant form of football in Canada, is closely related to American football—both sports developed from rugby and are considered to be the chief variants of gridiron football.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The Canadian Football League (CFL) is the major Canadian league and is the second-most popular sporting league in Canada, behind the National Hockey League.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Football Canada is the governing body for amateur Canadian football, and is also member of the International Federation of American Football.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] NFL players have played in the CFL and vice versa; quarterback Warren Moon is the only player in both Canadian Football Hall of Fame and the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The NFL and CFL had a formal working relationship from 1997 to 2006.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The CFL has a strategic partnership with two American football leagues, the German Football League (GFL) and the Liga de Futbol Americano Profesional (LFA).
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Rule changes announced in 2025 by the CFL will bring some elements of the sport closer to those of American football, while retaining the larger number of players, wider field, and three-down limit.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The Indoor Football League is an example of a prominent indoor league.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] The Arena Football League, which was founded in 1987 and ceased operations in 2019, was one of the longest-lived indoor football leagues.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] In 2004, the league was called "America's fifth major sport" by *ESPN The Magazine*.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Some schools that lack the enrollment numbers to run a competitive 11-man team choose to play nine-man, eight-man, or six-man football, which utilize modified rules to account for smaller team sizes.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] There are several non-contact variants of football, such as flag football.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] In flag football the ball-carrier is not tackled; instead, defenders aim to pull a flag tied around the ball-carrier's waist.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Flag football has become increasingly popular due to its lower likelihood of head injuries and its openness to female athletes; according to the NFL, which promotes flag football through NFL Flag, roughly 25% of flag football players are women and girls.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Another variant, touch football, simply requires the ball-carrier to be touched to be considered downed.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Depending on the rules used, a game of touch football may require the ball-carrier be touched with either one or two hands to be considered downed.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Wheelchair football is a parasport adapting the rules of football for people with physical disabilities.
[src:boules/american-football-p02] Although it uses touch rules instead of tackling, wheelchair football isn't a non-contact sport; participants engage in both "big hits" and "physical blocks".
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Three centuries after the decline of Mycenaean Greece during the Bronze Age collapse, Greek urban poleis began to form in the 8th century BC, ushering in the Archaic period and the colonization of the Mediterranean Basin.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] This was followed by the age of Classical Greece, from the Greco-Persian Wars to the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC, and which included the Golden Age of Athens and the Peloponnesian War between Athens and Sparta.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The unification of Greece by Macedon under Philip II and subsequent conquest of the Achaemenid Empire by Alexander the Great spread Hellenistic civilization across the Middle East.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Hellenistic period is considered to have ended in 30 BC, when the last Hellenistic kingdom, Ptolemaic Egypt, was annexed by the Roman Republic.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Classical Greek culture, especially Greek philosophy, had a powerful influence on ancient Rome, which carried a version of it throughout the Mediterranean and much of Europe.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] For this reason, Classical Greece is generally considered the cradle of Western civilization, the seminal culture from which the modern West derives many of its founding archetypes and ideas in politics, philosophy, science, and art.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Classical antiquity in the Mediterranean region is commonly considered to have begun in the 8th century BC (around the time of the earliest recorded poetry of Homer) and ended in the 6th century AD.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Classical antiquity in Greece was preceded by the Greek Dark Ages (c.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] 800 BC), archaeologically characterised by the protogeometric and geometric styles of designs on pottery.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Following the Dark Ages was the Archaic period, beginning around the 8th century BC, which saw early developments in Greek culture and society leading to the Classical period from the Persian invasion of Greece in 480 BC until the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Classical period is characterized by a "classical" style, i.e. one which was considered exemplary by later observers, most famously in the Parthenon of Athens.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Politically, the Classical period was dominated by Athens and the Delian League during the 5th century, but displaced by Spartan hegemony during the early 4th century BC, before power shifted to Thebes and the Boeotian League and finally to the League of Corinth led by Macedon.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] This period was shaped by the Greco-Persian Wars, the Peloponnesian War, and the Rise of Macedon.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Following the Classical period was the Hellenistic period (323–146 BC), during which Greek culture and power expanded into the Near East from the death of Alexander until the Roman conquest.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Roman Greece is usually counted from the Roman victory over the Corinthians at the Battle of Corinth in 146 BC to the establishment of Byzantium by Constantine as the capital of the Roman Empire in 330 AD.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Finally, Late Antiquity refers to the period of Christianization during the later 4th to early 6th centuries AD, consummated by the closure of the Academy of Athens by Justinian I in 529.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The historical period of ancient Greece is unique in world history as the first period attested directly in comprehensive, narrative historiography, while earlier ancient history or protohistory is known from much more fragmentary documents such as annals, king lists, and pragmatic epigraphy.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Herodotus is widely known as the "father of history": his *Histories* are eponymous of the entire field.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Written between the 450s and 420s BC, Herodotus' work reaches about a century into the past, discussing 6th-century BC historical figures such as Darius I of Persia, Cambyses II and Psamtik III, and alluding to some 8th-century BC persons such as Candaules.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The accuracy of Herodotus' works is debated.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Herodotus was succeeded by authors such as Thucydides, Xenophon, Demosthenes, Plato and Aristotle.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Most were either Athenian or pro-Athenian, which is why far more is known about the history and politics of Athens than of many other cities.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Their scope is further limited by a focus on political, military and diplomatic history, ignoring economic and social history.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The archaic period, lasting approximately from 800 to 500 BC, saw the culmination of political and social developments which had begun in the Greek Dark Age, with the *polis* (city-state) becoming the most important unit of political organisation in Greece.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The absence of powerful states in Greece after the collapse of Mycenaean power, and the geography of Greece, where many settlements were separated from their neighbours by mountainous terrain, encouraged the development of small independent city-states.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Several Greek states saw tyrants rise to power in this period, most famously at Corinth from 657 BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The period also saw the founding of Greek colonies around the Mediterranean, with Euboean settlements at Al-Mina in the east as early as 800 BC, and Ischia in the west by 775.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Increasing contact with non-Greek peoples in this period, especially in the Near East, inspired developments in art and architecture, the adoption of coinage, and the development of the Greek alphabet.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Athens developed its democratic system over the course of the archaic period.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Already in the 7th century, the right of all citizen men to attend the assembly appears to have been established.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] After a failed coup led by Cylon of Athens around 636 BC, Draco was appointed to establish a code of laws in 621.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] This failed to reduce the political tension between the poor and the elites, and in 594 Solon was given the authority to enact another set of reforms, which attempted to balance the power of the rich and the poor.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the middle of the 6th century, Pisistratus established himself as a tyrant, and after his death in 527 his son Hippias inherited his position; by the end of the 6th century he had been overthrown, and Cleisthenes carried out further democratising reforms.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In Sparta, a political system with two kings, a council of elders, and five ephors developed over the course of the 8th and 7th centuries.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] According to Spartan tradition, this constitution was established by the legendary lawgiver Lycurgus.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Over the course of the First Messenian War and Second Messenian War, Sparta subjugated the neighbouring region of Messenia, enserfing the population.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the 6th century, Greek city-states began to develop formal relationships with one another, where previously individual rulers had relied on personal relationships with the elites of other cities.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Towards the end of the Archaic period, Sparta began to build a series of alliances, the Peloponnesian League, with cities including Corinth, Elis, and Megara, isolating Messenia and reinforcing Sparta's position against Argos, the other major power in the Peloponnese.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Other alliances in the 6th century included those between Elis and Heraea in the Peloponnese; and between the Greek colony Sybaris in southern Italy, its allies, and the Serdaioi.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In 499 BC, the Ionian city-states under Persian rule rebelled against their Persian-supported tyrant rulers.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Supported by troops sent from Athens and Eretria, they advanced as far as Sardis and burnt the city before being driven back by a Persian counterattack.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The revolt continued until 494, when the rebelling Ionians were defeated.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Darius did not forget that Athens had assisted the Ionian revolt, and in 490 he assembled an armada to retaliate.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Though heavily outnumbered, the Athenians—supported by their Plataean allies—defeated the Persian hordes at the Battle of Marathon, and the Persian fleet turned tail.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Ten years later, a second invasion was launched by Darius' son Xerxes.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The city-states of northern and central Greece submitted to the Persian forces without resistance, but a coalition of 31 Greek city-states, including Athens and Sparta, determined to resist the Persian invaders.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] At the same time, Greek Sicily was invaded by a Carthaginian force.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Persians were decisively defeated at sea by a primarily Athenian naval force at the Battle of Salamis, and on land in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The alliance against Persia continued, initially led by the Spartan Pausanias but from 477 by Athens, and by 460 Persia had been driven out of the Aegean.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] During this long campaign, the Delian League gradually transformed from a defensive alliance of Greek states into an Athenian empire, as Athens' growing naval power intimidated the other league states.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Athens ended its campaigns against Persia in 450, after a disastrous defeat in Egypt in 454, and the death of Cimon in action against the Persians on Cyprus in 450.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] As the Athenian fight against the Persian empire waned, conflict grew between Athens and Sparta.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Suspicious of the increasing Athenian power funded by the Delian League, Sparta offered aid to reluctant members of the League to rebel against Athenian domination.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] These tensions were exacerbated in 462 BC when Athens sent a force to aid Sparta in overcoming a helot revolt, but this aid was rejected by the Spartans.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the 450s, Athens took control of Boeotia, and won victories over Aegina and Corinth.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] However, Athens failed to win a decisive victory, and in 447 lost Boeotia again.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Athens and Sparta signed the Thirty Years' Peace in the winter of 446/445, ending the conflict.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Despite the treaty, Athenian relations with Sparta declined again in the 430s, and in 431 BC the Peloponnesian War began.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The first phase of the war saw a series of fruitless annual invasions of Attica by Sparta, while Athens successfully fought the Corinthian empire in northwest Greece and defended its own empire, despite a plague which killed the leading Athenian statesman Pericles.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The war turned after Athenian victories led by Cleon at Pylos and Sphakteria, and Sparta sued for peace, but the Athenians rejected the proposal.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Athenian failure to regain control of Boeotia at Delium and Brasidas' successes in northern Greece in 424 improved Sparta's position after Sphakteria.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] After the deaths of Cleon and Brasidas, the strongest proponents of war on each side, a peace treaty was negotiated in 421 by the Athenian general Nicias.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In 418 BC allied forces of Athens and Argos were defeated by Sparta at Mantinea.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In 415 Athens launched an ambitious naval expedition to dominate Sicily; the expedition ended in disaster at the harbor of Syracuse, with almost the entire army killed, and the ships destroyed.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Soon after the Athenian defeat in Syracuse, Athens' Ionian allies began to rebel against the Delian league, while Persia began to once again involve itself in Greek affairs on the Spartan side.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Initially the Athenian position continued relatively strong, with important victories at Cyzicus in 410 and Arginusae in 406.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] However, in 405 the Spartan Lysander defeated Athens in the Battle of Aegospotami, and began to blockade Athens' harbour; driven by hunger, Athens sued for peace, agreeing to surrender their fleet and join the Spartan-led Peloponnesian League.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Following the Athenian surrender, Sparta installed an oligarchic regime, the Thirty Tyrants, in Athens, one of a number of Spartan-backed oligarchies which rose to power after the Peloponnesian war.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Spartan predominance did not last: after only a year, the Thirty had been overthrown.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The first half of the 4th century saw the major Greek states attempt to dominate the mainland; none were successful, and their resulting weakness led to a power vacuum which was eventually filled by Macedon under Philip II and then Alexander the Great.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the immediate aftermath of the Peloponnesian war, Sparta attempted to extend their own power, leading Argos, Athens, Corinth, and Thebes to join against them.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Aiming to prevent any single Greek state gaining the dominance that would allow it to challenge Persia, the Persian king initially joined the alliance against Sparta, before imposing the Peace of Antalcidas ("King's Peace") which restored Persia's control over the Anatolian Greeks.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] By 371 BC, Thebes was in the ascendancy, defeating Sparta at the Battle of Leuctra, killing the Spartan king Cleombrotus I, and invading Laconia.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Further Theban successes against Sparta in 369 led to Messenia gaining independence; Sparta never recovered from the loss of Messenia's fertile land and the helot workforce it provided.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The rising power of Thebes led Sparta and Athens to join forces; in 362 they were defeated by Thebes at the Battle of Mantinea.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the aftermath of Mantinea, none of the major Greek states were able to dominate.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Though Thebes had won the battle, their general Epaminondas was killed, and they spent the following decades embroiled in wars with their neighbours; Athens, meanwhile, saw its second naval alliance, formed in 377, collapse in the mid-350s.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The power vacuum in Greece after the Battle of Mantinea was filled by Macedon, under Philip II, starting from the battle of Crocus field.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In 338 BC, he defeated a Greek alliance at the Battle of Chaeronea, and subsequently formed the League of Corinth.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Philip planned to lead the League to invade Persia, but was murdered in 336 BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] His son Alexander the Great was left to fulfill his father's ambitions.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] After campaigns against Macedon's western and northern enemies, and those Greek states that had broken from the League of Corinth following the death of Philip, Alexander began his campaign against Persia in 334 BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] He conquered Persia, defeating Darius III at the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, and after the Battle of Gaugamela in 331 BC proclaimed himself king of Asia.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] From 329 BC he led expeditions to Bactria and then India; further plans to invade Arabia and North Africa were halted by his death in 323 BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The period from the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC until the death of Cleopatra, the last Macedonian ruler of Egypt, is known as the Hellenistic period.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the early part of this period, a new form of kingship developed based on Macedonian and Near Eastern traditions.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The first Hellenistic kings were previously Alexander's generals, and took power in the period following his death, though they were not part of existing royal lineages and lacked historic claims to the territories they controlled.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the early part of the Hellenistic period, the exact borders of the Hellenistic kingdoms were not settled.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Antigonus attempted to expand his territory by attacking the other successor kingdoms until they joined against him, and he was killed at the Battle of Ipsus in 301 BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] His son Demetrius spent many years in Seleucid captivity, and his son, Antigonus II, only reclaimed the Macedonian throne around 276.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Meanwhile, the Seleucid kingdom gave up territory in the east to the Indian king Chandragupta Maurya in exchange for war elephants, and later lost large parts of Persia to the Parthian Empire.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] By the mid-3rd century, the kingdoms of Alexander's successors was mostly stable, though there continued to be disputes over border areas.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The great capitals of Hellenistic culture were Alexandria in the Ptolemaic Kingdom and Antioch in the Seleucid Empire.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The conquests of Alexander had numerous consequences for the Greek city-states.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] It greatly widened the horizons of the Greeks and led to a steady emigration of the young and ambitious to the new Greek empires in the east.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Many Greeks migrated to Alexandria, Antioch and the many other new Hellenistic cities founded in Alexander's wake, as far away as present-day Afghanistan and Pakistan, where the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom and the Indo-Greek Kingdom survived until the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Some city-states within Greece formed themselves into two major leagues; the Achaean League (including Corinth and Argos) and the Aetolian League.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] For much of the period until the Roman conquest, these leagues were at war, often participating in the conflicts between the Diadochi's successor states to Alexander's empire.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Antigonid Kingdom became involved in a war with the Roman Republic in the late 3rd century.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Although the First Macedonian War was inconclusive, the Romans, in typical fashion, continued to fight Macedon until it was completely absorbed into the Roman Republic (by 149 BC).
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the east, the unwieldy Seleucid Empire gradually disintegrated, although a rump survived until 64 BC, whilst the Ptolemaic Kingdom continued in Egypt until 30 BC when it too was conquered by the Romans.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Aetolian league grew wary of Roman involvement in Greece, and sided with the Seleucids in the Roman–Seleucid War; when the Romans were victorious, the league was effectively absorbed into the Republic.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Although the Achaean league outlasted both the Aetolian league and Macedon, it was also soon defeated and absorbed by the Romans in 146 BC, bringing Greek independence to an end.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Greek peninsula came under Roman rule during the 146 BC conquest of Greece after the Battle of Corinth.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Macedonia became a Roman province while southern Greece came under the surveillance of Macedonia's prefect; however, some Greek *poleis* managed to maintain a partial independence and avoid taxation.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Aegean Islands were added to this territory in 133 BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Athens and other Greek cities revolted in 88 BC, and the peninsula was crushed by the Roman general Sulla.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Roman civil wars devastated the land even further, until Augustus organized the peninsula as the province of Achaea in 27 BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Greece was a key eastern province of the Roman Empire, as the Roman culture had long been in fact Greco-Roman.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Greek language served as a *lingua franca* in the East and in Italy, and many Greek intellectuals such as Galen would perform most of their work in Rome.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The territory of Greece is mountainous, and as a result, ancient Greece consisted of many smaller regions, each with its own dialect, cultural peculiarities, and identity.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Regionalism and regional conflicts were prominent features of ancient Greece.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Cities tended to be located in valleys between mountains, or on coastal plains, and dominated a certain area around them.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the south lay the Peloponnese, consisting of the regions of Laconia (southeast), Messenia (southwest), Elis (west), Achaia (north), Korinthia (northeast), Argolis (east), and Arcadia (center).
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] These names survive to the present day as regional units of modern Greece, though with somewhat different boundaries.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Mainland Greece to the north, nowadays known as Central Greece, consisted of Aetolia and Acarnania in the west, Locris, Doris, and Phocis in the center, while in the east lay Boeotia, Attica, and Megaris.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Northeast lay Thessaly, while Epirus lay to the northwest.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Epirus stretched from the Ambracian Gulf in the south to the Ceraunian Mountains and the Aoos river in the north, and consisted of Chaonia (north), Molossia (center), and Thesprotia (south).
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the northeast corner was Macedonia, originally consisting Lower Macedonia and its regions, such as Emathia (Macedonia), Pieria, and Bottiaea, and later Almopia, Amphaxitis.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The original capital of Macedon was Aigai and then moved to Pella in the 4th century BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] To the north of Macedonia lay various non-Greek peoples such as the Paeonians due north, the Thracians to the northeast, and the Illyrians, with whom the Macedonians were frequently in conflict, to the northwest.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Chalcidice was settled early on by southern Greek colonists and was considered part of the Greek world, while from the late 2nd millennium BC substantial Greek settlement also occurred on the eastern shores of the Aegean, in Anatolia.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] This was not simply for trade, but also to found settlements.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] These Greek colonies were not, as Roman colonies were, dependent on their mother-city, but were independent city-states in their own right.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Greeks settled outside of Greece in two distinct ways.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The first was in permanent settlements founded by Greeks, which formed as independent poleis.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The second form was in what historians refer to as *emporia*; trading posts which were occupied by both Greeks and non-Greeks and which were primarily concerned with the manufacture and sale of goods.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Examples of this latter type of settlement are found at Al Mina in the east and Pithekoussai in the west.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] From around 750 to 500 BC, Greeks settled colonies in all directions.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] To the east, the Aegean coast of Asia Minor was colonized first, followed by Cyprus and the coasts of Thrace, the Sea of Marmara and the south coast of the Black Sea.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Eventually, Greek colonization reached as far northeast as present-day Ukraine and Russia (Taganrog).
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] To the west the coasts of Illyria, Southern Italy (called "Magna Graecia") were settled, followed by Southern France, Corsica, and even eastern Spain.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Greek colonies were also founded in Egypt and Libya.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Modern Syracuse, Naples, Marseille and Istanbul had their beginnings as the Greek colonies Syracusae (Συράκουσαι), Neapolis (Νεάπολις), Massalia (Μασσαλία) and Byzantion (Βυζάντιον).
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] These colonies played an important role in the spread of Greek influence throughout Europe and also aided in the establishment of long-distance trading networks between the Greek city-states, boosting the economy of ancient Greece.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Ancient Greece consisted of several hundred relatively independent city-states (*poleis*).
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] This was a situation unlike that in most other contemporary societies, which were either tribal or kingdoms ruling over relatively large territories.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Undoubtedly, the geography of Greece—divided and sub-divided by hills, mountains, and rivers—contributed to the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] On the one hand, the ancient Greeks had no doubt that they were "one people"; they had the same religion, same basic culture, and same language.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Furthermore, the Greeks were very aware of their tribal origins; Herodotus was able to extensively categorise the city-states by tribe.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Yet, although these higher-level relationships existed, they seem to have rarely had a major role in Greek politics.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The independence of the *poleis* was fiercely defended; unification was something rarely contemplated by the ancient Greeks.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Even when, during the second Persian invasion of Greece, a group of city-states allied themselves to defend Greece, the vast majority of *poleis* remained neutral, and after the Persian defeat, the allies quickly returned to infighting.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Thus, the major peculiarities of the ancient Greek political system were its fragmented nature (and that this does not particularly seem to have tribal origin), and the particular focus on urban centers within otherwise tiny states.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The peculiarities of the Greek system are further evidenced by the colonies that they set up throughout the Mediterranean, which, though they might count a certain Greek *polis* as their 'mother' (and remain sympathetic to her), were completely independent of the founding city.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Inevitably smaller *poleis* might be dominated by larger neighbors, but conquest or direct rule by another city-state appears to have been quite rare.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Instead the *poleis* grouped themselves into leagues, membership of which was in a constant state of flux.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Later in the Classical period, the leagues would become fewer and larger, be dominated by one city (particularly Athens, Sparta and Thebes); and often *poleis* would be compelled to join under threat of war (or as part of a peace treaty).
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Even after Philip II of Macedon conquered the heartlands of ancient Greece, he did not attempt to annex the territory or unify it into a new province, but compelled most of the *poleis* to join his own Corinthian League.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Initially many Greek city-states seem to have been petty kingdoms; there was often a city official carrying some residual, ceremonial functions of the king (*basileus*), e.g., the *archon basileus* in Athens.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] However, by the Archaic period and the first historical consciousness, most had already become aristocratic oligarchies.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] It is unclear exactly how this change occurred.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] For instance, in Athens, the kingship had been reduced to a hereditary, lifelong chief magistracy (*archon*) by c.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] 1050 BC; by 753 BC this had become a decennial, elected archonship, and finally an annually elected archonship by 683 BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Through each stage, more power would have been transferred to the aristocracy as a whole, and away from a single individual.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Inevitably, the domination of politics and concomitant aggregation of wealth by small groups of families was apt to cause social unrest in many *poleis*.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In many cities a tyrant (not in the modern sense of repressive autocracies), would at some point seize control and govern according to their own will; often a populist agenda would help sustain them in power.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In a system wracked with class conflict, government by a 'strongman' was often the best solution.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Athens fell under a tyranny in the second half of the 6th century BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] When this tyranny was ended, the Athenians founded the world's first democracy as a radical solution to prevent the aristocracy regaining power.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] A citizens' assembly (the *Ecclesia*), for the discussion of city policy, had existed since the reforms of Draco in 621 BC; all citizens were permitted to attend after the reforms of Solon (early 6th century), but the poorest citizens could not address the assembly or run for office.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] With the establishment of the democracy, the assembly became the *de jure* mechanism of government; all citizens had equal privileges in the assembly.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] However, non-citizens, such as metics (foreigners living in Athens) or slaves, had no political rights at all.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] After the rise of democracy in Athens, other city-states founded democracies.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] However, many retained more traditional forms of government.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] As so often in other matters, Sparta was a notable exception to the rest of Greece, ruled through the whole period by not one, but two hereditary monarchs.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Kings of Sparta belonged to the Agiads and the Eurypontids, descendants respectively of Eurysthenes and Procles.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Both dynasties' founders were believed to be twin sons of Aristodemus, a Heraclid ruler.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] However, the powers of these kings were held in check by both a council of elders (the *Gerousia*) and magistrates specifically appointed to watch over the kings (the *Ephors*).
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Only free, land-owning, native-born men could be citizens entitled to the full protection of the law in a city-state.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In most city-states, unlike the situation in Rome, social prominence did not allow special rights.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Sometimes families controlled public religious functions, but this ordinarily did not give any extra power in the government.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In Athens, the population was divided into four social classes based on wealth.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] People could change classes if they made more money.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In Sparta, all male citizens were called *homoioi*, meaning "peers".
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] However, Spartan kings, who served as the city-state's dual military and religious leaders, came from two families.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Women in Ancient Greece appear to have primarily performed domestic tasks, managed households, and borne and reared children.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Slaves had the right to have a family and own property, subject to their master's goodwill and permission, but they had no political rights.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] By 600 BC, chattel slavery had spread in Greece.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] By the 5th century BC, slaves made up one-third of the total population in some city-states.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Between 40 and 80% of the population of Classical Athens were slaves.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Slaves outside of Sparta almost never revolted because they were made up of too many nationalities and were too scattered to organize.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] However, unlike later Western culture, the ancient Greeks did not think in terms of race.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Most families owned slaves as household servants and laborers, and even poor families might have owned a few slaves.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Owners were not allowed to beat or kill their slaves.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Owners often promised to free slaves in the future to encourage slaves to work hard.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Unlike in Rome, freedmen did not become citizens.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Instead, they were mixed into the population of *metics*, which included people from foreign countries or other city-states who were officially allowed to live in the state.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] These public slaves had a larger measure of independence than slaves owned by families, living on their own and performing specialized tasks.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In Athens, public slaves were trained to look out for counterfeit coinage, while temple slaves acted as servants of the temple's deity and Scythian slaves were employed in Athens as a police force corralling citizens to political functions.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Sparta had a special type of slaves called *helots*.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Helots were Messenians enslaved en masse during the Messenian Wars by the state and assigned to families where they were forced to stay.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Helots raised food and did household chores so that women could concentrate on raising strong children while men could devote their time to training as hoplites.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Their masters treated them harshly, and helots revolted against their masters several times.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In 370/369 BC, as a result of Epaminondas' liberation of Messenia from Spartan rule, the helot system there came to an end and the helots won their freedom.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] However, it persisted in Laconia until the 2nd century BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] For most of Greek history, education was private, except in Sparta.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] During the Hellenistic period, some city-states established public schools.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Only wealthy families could afford a teacher.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Boys learned how to read, write and quote literature.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] They also learned to sing and play one musical instrument and were trained as athletes for military service.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] They studied not for a job but to become an effective citizen.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Girls also learned to read, write and do simple arithmetic so they could manage the household.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] They almost never received education after childhood.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Boys went to school at the age of seven, or went to the barracks, if they lived in Sparta.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The three types of teachings were: grammatistes for arithmetic, kitharistes for music and dancing, and Paedotribae for sports.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Boys from wealthy families attending the private school lessons were taken care of by a *paidagogos*, a household slave selected for this task who accompanied the boy during the day.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Classes were held in teachers' private houses and included reading, writing, mathematics, singing, and playing the lyre and flute.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] When the boy became 12 years old the schooling started to include sports such as wrestling, running, and throwing discus and javelin.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In Athens, some older youths attended academy for the finer disciplines such as culture, sciences, music, and the arts.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The schooling ended at age 18, followed by military training in the army usually for one or two years.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Some of Athens' greatest such schools included the Lyceum (the so-called Peripatetic school founded by Aristotle of Stageira) and the Platonic Academy (founded by Plato of Athens).
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The education system of the wealthy ancient Greeks is also called Paideia.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] At its economic height in the 5th and 4th centuries BC, the free citizenry of Classical Greece represented perhaps the most prosperous society in the ancient world, some economic historians considering Greece one of the most advanced pre-industrial economies.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In terms of wheat, wages reached an estimated 7–12 kg (15–26 lb) daily for an unskilled worker in urban Athens, 2–3 times the 3.75 kg (8.3 lb) of an unskilled rural labourer in Roman Egypt, though Greek farm incomes too were on average lower than those available to urban workers.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] At least in the Archaic period, the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece, with many competing city-states, increased the frequency of conflict but conversely limited the scale of warfare.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Unable to maintain professional armies, the city-states relied on their own citizens to fight.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] This inevitably reduced the potential duration of campaigns, as citizens would need to return to their own professions (especially in the case of, for example, farmers).
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Campaigns would therefore often be restricted to summer.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] When battles occurred, they were usually set piece and intended to be decisive.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Casualties were slight compared to later battles, rarely amounting to more than five percent of the losing side, but the slain often included the most prominent citizens and generals who led from the front.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The scale and scope of warfare in ancient Greece changed dramatically as a result of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] To fight the enormous armies of the Achaemenid Empire was effectively beyond the capabilities of a single city-state.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The eventual triumph of the Greeks was achieved by alliances of city-states (the exact composition changing over time), allowing the pooling of resources and division of labor.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Although alliances between city-states occurred before this time, nothing on this scale had been seen before.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The rise of Athens and Sparta as pre-eminent powers during this conflict led directly to the Peloponnesian War, which saw further development of the nature of warfare, strategy and tactics.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Fought between leagues of cities dominated by Athens and Sparta, the increased manpower and financial resources increased the scale and allowed the diversification of warfare.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Set-piece battles during the Peloponnesian war proved indecisive and instead there was increased reliance on attritionary strategies, naval battles and blockades and sieges.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] These changes greatly increased the number of casualties and the disruption of Greek society.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Athens owned one of the largest war fleets in ancient Greece.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] It had over 200 triremes each powered by 170 oarsmen who were seated in 3 rows on each side of the ship.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The city could afford such a large fleet—it had over 34,000 oarsmen—because it owned a lot of silver mines that were worked by slaves.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] According to Josiah Ober, Greek city-states faced approximately a one-in-three chance of destruction during the archaic and classical period.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Ancient Greek philosophy focused on the role of reason and inquiry.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In many ways, it had an important influence on modern philosophy, as well as modern science.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Clear unbroken lines of influence lead from ancient Greek and Hellenistic philosophers, to medieval Muslim philosophers and Islamic scientists, to the European Renaissance and Enlightenment, to the secular sciences of the modern day.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Neither reason nor inquiry began with the ancient Greeks.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Defining the difference between the Greek quest for knowledge and the quests of the elder civilizations, such as the ancient Egyptians and Babylonians, has long been a topic of study by theorists of civilization.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The first known philosophers of Greece were the pre-Socratics, who attempted to provide naturalistic, non-mythical descriptions of the world.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] They were followed by Socrates, one of the first philosophers based in Athens during its golden age whose ideas, despite being known by second-hand accounts instead of writings of his own, laid the basis of Western philosophy.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Socrates' disciple Plato, who wrote *The Republic* and established a radical difference between ideas and the concrete world, and Plato's disciple Aristotle, who wrote extensively about nature and ethics, are also immensely influential in Western philosophy to this day.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The later Hellenistic philosophy, also originating in Greece, is defined by names such as Antisthenes (cynicism), Zeno of Citium (stoicism) and Plotinus (Neoplatonism).
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The earliest Greek literature was poetry and was composed for performance rather than private consumption.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The earliest Greek poet known is Homer, although he was certainly part of an existing tradition of oral poetry.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Homer's poetry, though it was developed around the same time that the Greeks developed writing, would have been composed orally; the first poet to certainly compose their work in writing was Archilochus, a lyric poet from the mid-7th century BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Tragedy developed around the end of the archaic period, taking elements from across the pre-existing genres of late archaic poetry.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Like poetry, Greek prose had its origins in the archaic period, and the earliest writers of Greek philosophy, history, and medical literature all date to the 6th century BC.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Prose first emerged as the writing style adopted by the presocratic philosophers Anaximander and Anaximenes—though Thales of Miletus, considered the first Greek philosopher, apparently wrote nothing.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Prose as a genre reached maturity in the classical era, and the major Greek prose genres—philosophy, history, rhetoric, and dialogue—developed in this period.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Hellenistic period saw the literary centre of the Greek world move from Athens, where it had been in the classical period, to Alexandria.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] At the same time, other Hellenistic kings such as the Antigonids and the Attalids were patrons of scholarship and literature, turning Pella and Pergamon respectively into cultural centres.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] It was thanks to this cultural patronage by Hellenistic kings, and especially the Museum at Alexandria, that so much ancient Greek literature has survived.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Library of Alexandria, part of the Museum, had the previously unenvisaged aim of collecting together copies of all known authors in Greek.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Almost all of the surviving non-technical Hellenistic literature is poetry, and Hellenistic poetry tended to be highly intellectual, blending different genres and traditions, and avoiding linear narratives.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Hellenistic period also saw a shift in the ways literature was consumed—while in the archaic and classical periods literature had typically been experienced in public performance, in the Hellenistic period it was more commonly read privately.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] At the same time, Hellenistic poets began to write for private, rather than public, consumption.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] With Octavian's victory at Actium in 31 BC, Rome began to become a major centre of Greek literature, as important Greek authors such as Strabo and Dionysius of Halicarnassus came to Rome.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The period of greatest innovation in Greek literature under Rome was the "long second century" from approximately 80 AD to around 230 AD.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] This innovation was especially marked in prose, with the development of the novel and a revival of prominence for display oratory both dating to this period.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In Ancient Greek society, music was ever-present and considered a fundamental component of civilisation.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] It was an important part of public religious worship, private ceremonies such as weddings and funerals, and household entertainment.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Men sang and played music at the symposium; both men and women sang at work; and children's games involved song and dance.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Ancient Greek music was primarily vocal, sung either by a solo singer or a chorus, and usually accompanied by an instrument; purely instrumental music was less common.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Greeks used stringed instruments, including lyres, harps, and lutes; and wind instruments, of which the most important was the *aulos*, a reed instrument.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Percussion instruments played a relatively unimportant role supporting stringed and wind instruments, and were used in certain religious cults.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Ancient Greek mathematics contributed many important developments to mathematics, including the basic rules of geometry, the idea of formal mathematical proof, and discoveries in number theory, mathematical analysis, applied mathematics, and approached close to establishing integral calculus.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The discoveries of several Greek mathematicians, including Pythagoras, Euclid, and Archimedes, are still used in mathematical teaching today.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Greeks developed astronomy, which they treated as a branch of mathematics, to a highly sophisticated level.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The first geometrical, three-dimensional models to explain the apparent motion of the planets were developed in the 4th century BC by Eudoxus of Cnidus and Callippus of Cyzicus.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Their younger contemporary Heraclides Ponticus proposed that the Earth rotates around its axis.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the 3rd century BC, Aristarchus of Samos was the first to suggest a heliocentric system.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Archimedes in his treatise The Sand Reckoner revives Aristarchus' hypothesis that *"the fixed stars and the Sun remain unmoved, while the Earth revolves about the Sun on the circumference of a circle"*.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Otherwise, only fragmentary descriptions of Aristarchus' idea survive.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Eratosthenes, using the angles of shadows created at widely separated regions, estimated the circumference of the Earth with great accuracy.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the 2nd century BC Hipparchus of Nicea made a number of contributions, including the first measurement of precession and the compilation of the first star catalog in which he proposed the modern system of apparent magnitudes.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Antikythera mechanism, a device for calculating the movements of planets, dates from about 80 BC and was the first ancestor of the astronomical computer.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] It was discovered in an ancient shipwreck off the Greek island of Antikythera, between Kythera and Crete.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The device became famous for its use of a differential gear, previously believed to have been invented in the 16th century, and the miniaturization and complexity of its parts, comparable to a clock made in the 18th century.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The original mechanism is displayed in the Bronze collection of the National Archaeological Museum of Athens, accompanied by a replica.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The ancient Greeks also made important discoveries in the medical field.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Hippocrates was a physician of the Classical period, and is considered one of the most outstanding figures in the history of medicine.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] He is referred to as the "father of medicine" in recognition of his lasting contributions to the field as the founder of the Hippocratic school of medicine.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] This intellectual school revolutionized medicine in ancient Greece, establishing it as a discipline distinct from other fields that it had traditionally been associated with (notably theurgy and philosophy), thus making medicine a profession.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The art of ancient Greece has exercised an enormous influence on the culture of many countries from ancient times to the present day, particularly in the areas of sculpture and architecture.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the West, the art of the Roman Empire was largely derived from Greek models.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] In the East, Alexander the Great's conquests initiated several centuries of exchange between Greek, Central Asian and Indian cultures, resulting in Greco-Buddhist art, with ramifications as far as Japan.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Following the Renaissance in Europe, the humanist aesthetic and the high technical standards of Greek art inspired generations of European artists.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Well into the 19th century, the classical tradition derived from Greece dominated the art of the Western world.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Religion was a central part of ancient Greek life.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Though the Greeks of different cities and tribes worshipped similar gods, religious practices were not uniform and the gods were thought of differently in different places.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The Greeks were polytheistic, worshipping many gods, but as early as the 6th century BC a pantheon of twelve Olympians began to develop.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Greek religion was influenced by the practices of the Greeks' near eastern neighbours at least as early as the archaic period, and by the Hellenistic period this influence was seen in both directions.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The most important religious act in ancient Greece was animal sacrifice, most commonly of sheep and goats.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Sacrifice was accompanied by public prayer, and prayer and hymns were themselves a major part of ancient Greek religious life.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] The civilization of ancient Greece has been immensely influential on language, politics, educational systems, philosophy, science, and the arts.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] It became the *Leitkultur* of the Roman Empire to the point of marginalizing native Italic traditions.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] Via the Roman Empire, Greek culture came to be foundational to Western culture in general.
[src:boules/ancient-greeks] A modern revival of Classical Greek learning took place in the Neoclassicism movement in 18th- and 19th-century Europe and the Americas.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The **Roman people** was the body of Roman citizens (Latin: *Rōmānī*; Ancient Greek: Ῥωμαῖοι *Rhōmaîoi*) during the Roman Kingdom, the Roman Republic, and the Roman Empire.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] This concept underwent considerable changes throughout the long history of the Roman civilisation, as its borders expanded and contracted.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Originally only including the ethnic Latins from Rome itself, Roman citizenship was extended to the rest of the Italic peoples by the 1st century BC and to nearly every subject of the Roman empire in late antiquity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] At their peak, the Romans ruled large parts of Europe, the Near East, and North Africa through conquests made during the Roman Republic and the subsequent Roman Empire.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Although defined primarily as a citizenship, "Roman-ness" has also and variously been described as a cultural identity, a nationality, or a multi-ethnicity that eventually encompassed a vast regional diversity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Citizenship grants, demographic growth, and settler and military colonies rapidly increased the number of Roman citizens.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The increase achieved its peak with Emperor Caracalla's AD 212 Antonine Constitution, which extended citizenship rights to all free inhabitants of the empire.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Roman identity provided a larger sense of common identity and became important when distinguishing from non-Romans, such as barbarian settlers and invaders.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Roman culture was far from homogeneous; though there was a common cultural idiom, one of the strengths of the Roman Empire was also its ability to incorporate traditions from other cultures, notably but not exclusively Greece.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The collapse of the Western Roman Empire in the 5th century ended the political domination of the Roman Empire in Western Europe, but Roman identity survived in the west as an important political resource.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In the Greek-speaking east, still under imperial control, Roman identity survived until the fall of the Byzantine Empire in 1453 and beyond.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Whereas Roman identity faded away in most of the lands where it was once prominent, for some regions and peoples it proved considerably more tenacious.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In Italy, "Romans" (*Romani* in Latin and Italian) has continuously and uninterruptedly been the demonym of the citizens of Rome from the foundation of the city to the present-day.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] During the Eastern Roman Empire and for centuries after its fall, Greeks largely identified as "Romans" (*Rōmaîoi* or *Romioi* in transliterated Greek), even referring to vernacular Greek as the "Roman language" (*Romaiki glossa*).
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In Switzerland several names are Roman references: the Romands and the Romansh people.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Several names derive from the Latin *Romani* (such as the Romanians, Aromanians and Istro-Romanians), or from the Germanic *walhaz* (a term originally referring to the Romans; adopted in the form *Vlach* as the self-designation of the Megleno-Romanians).
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The term 'Roman' is today used interchangeably to describe a historical timespan, a material culture, a geographical location, and a personal identity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Though these concepts are related, they are not identical.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Many modern historians tend to have a preferred idea of what being Roman meant, so-called *Romanitas*, but this was a term rarely used in Ancient Rome itself.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Like all identities, the identity of 'Roman' was flexible, dynamic and multi-layered, and never static or unchanging.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Given that Rome was a geographically vast and chronologically long-lived state, there is no simple definition of what being Roman meant and definitions were inconsistent already in antiquity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Nevertheless, some elements remained common throughout much of Roman history.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Some ancient Romans considered aspects such as geography, language, and ethnicity as important markers of Romanness, whereas others saw Roman citizenship and culture or behaviour as more important.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] At the height of the Roman Empire, Roman identity formed a collective geopolitical identity, extended to nearly all subjects of the Roman emperors and encompassing vast regional and ethnical diversity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Often, what individual believed and did was far more important to the concept of Roman identity than long bloodlines and shared descent.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The key to 'Romanness' in the minds of some famous Roman orators, such as Cicero, was keeping with Roman tradition and serving the Roman state.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Cicero's view of Romanness were partly formed by his status as a "new man", the first of his family to serve in the Roman Senate, lacking prestigious lines of Roman descent himself.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] This is not to say that the importance of blood kinship was wholly dismissed.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Orators such as Cicero frequently appealed to their noble contemporaries to live up to the 'greatness of their forefathers'.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] These appeals were typically only invoked towards illustrious noble families, with other important traditions emphasising Rome's collective descent.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Throughout its history, Rome proved to be uniquely capable of incorporating and integrating other peoples (Romanisation).
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] This sentiment originated from the city's foundation myths, including Rome being founded as something akin to a political sanctuary by Romulus, as well as the rape of the Sabine women, which represented how different peoples had commingled since the very beginning of the city.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Cicero and other Roman authors sneered at peoples such as the Athenians, who prided themselves in their shared descent, and instead found pride in Rome's status as a "mongrel nation".
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] A handful of Roman authors, such as Tacitus and Suetonius, expressed concerns in their writings regarding Roman "blood purity" as Roman citizens from outside of Roman Italy increased in number.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Neither author, however, suggested that the naturalisation of new citizens should stop, only that manumissions (freeing slaves) and grants of citizenship should be less frequent.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Their concerns of blood purity did not match modern ideas of race or ethnicity, and had little to do with features such as skin colour or physical appearance.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The main dividing social differences in Ancient Rome were not based on physical features, but rather on differences in class or rank.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Romans practised slavery extensively, but slaves in Ancient Rome were part of various different ethnic groups, and were not enslaved because of their ethnic affiliation.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] According to the English historian Emma Dench, it was "notoriously difficult to detect slaves by their appearance" in Ancient Rome.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Although Ancient Rome has been termed an 'evidently non-racist society', Romans carried considerable cultural stereotypes and prejudices against cultures and peoples that were not integrated into the Roman world, i.e.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Though views differed through Roman history, the attitude towards peoples beyond the Roman frontier among most Roman writers in late antiquity can be summed up with "the only good barbarian is a dead barbarian".
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Throughout antiquity, the majority of Roman emperors included anti-barbarian imagery on their coinage, such as the emperor or Victoria (the personification and goddess of victory) being depicted as stepping on or dragging defeated barbarian enemies.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Per the writings of Cicero, what made people barbarians was not their language or descent, but rather their customs and character, or lack thereof.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Romans viewed themselves as superior over foreigners, but this stemmed not from perceived biological differences, but rather from what they perceived as a superior way of life.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] 'Barbarian' was as such a cultural, rather than biological, term.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] It was not impossible for a barbarian to become a Roman; the Roman state was itself seen as having the duty to conquer and transform, i.e. civilise, barbarian peoples.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] A particularly disliked group of non-Romans within the empire were the Jews.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The majority of the Roman populace detested Jews and Judaism, though views were more varied among the Roman elite.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Although many, such as Tacitus, were also hostile to the Jews, others, such as Cicero, were merely unsympathetically indifferent.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The Roman state was not wholly opposed to the Jews, since there was a sizeable Jewish population in Rome itself, as well as at least thirteen synagogues in the city.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Roman antisemitism, which led to several wars, persecutions, and massacres in Judea, was not rooted in racial prejudice, but rather in the perception that the Jews, uniquely among conquered peoples, refused to integrate into the Roman world.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The Jews adhered to their own set of rules, restrictions and obligations, which were typically either disliked or misunderstood by the Romans, and they remained faithful to their own religion.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The exclusivist religious practices of the Jews, and their opposition to abandoning their own customs in favour of those of Rome, even after being conquered and repeatedly suppressed, evoked the suspicion of the Romans.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The founding of Rome, and the history of the city and its people throughout its first few centuries, is steeped in myth and uncertainty.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The traditional date for Rome's foundation, 753 BC, and the traditional date for the foundation of the Roman Republic, 509 BC, though commonly used even in modern historiography, are uncertain and mythical.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The actual mythical founder of the city itself, Romulus, only appears many generations into the complex web of foundation myths.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Interpretations of these myths varied among authors in Antiquity, but most agreed that their civilisation had been founded by a mixture of migrants and fugitives.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] These origin narratives would favour the later extensive integrations of foreigners into the Roman world.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The origins of the people that became the first Romans are clearer.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] As in neighbouring city-states, the early Romans were composed mainly of Latin-speaking Italic people, known as the Latins.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The Latins were a people with a marked Mediterranean character, related to other neighbouring Italic peoples such as the Falisci.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The early Romans were part of the Latin homeland, known as Latium, and were Latins themselves.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] From the middle of the 4th century onwards, Rome won a series of victories which saw them rise to rule all of Italy south of the Po river by 270 BC.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] By the late 3rd century BC, about a third of the people in Italy south of the Po river had been made Roman citizens, meaning that they were liable for military service, and the rest had been made into allies, frequently called on to join Roman wars.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] These allies were eventually made Roman citizens as well after refusal by the Roman government to make them so was met with the Social War, after which Roman citizenship was extended to all the people south of the Po river.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In 49 BC, citizenship rights were also extended to the people of Cisalpine Gaul by Julius Caesar.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The number of Romans would rapidly increase in later centuries through further extensions of citizenship.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Just as it could be gained, Roman status could also be lost, for instance through engaging practices considered corrupt or by being carried off into captivity in enemy raids (though one could again become a Roman upon returning from captivity).
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In the early Roman Empire, the population was composed of several groups of distinct legal standing, including the Roman citizens themselves (*cives romani*), the provincials (*provinciales*), foreigners (*peregrini*) and free non-citizens such as freedmen (freed slaves) and slaves.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Roman citizens were subject to the Roman legal system while provincials were subject to whatever laws and legal systems had been in place in their area at the time it was annexed by the Romans.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The capability of the Roman Empire to integrate foreign peoples was one of the key elements that ensured its success.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In antiquity, it was significantly easier as a foreigner to become a Roman than it was to become a member or citizen of any other contemporary state.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] This aspect of the Roman state was seen as important even by some of the emperors.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] From the Principate (27 BC – AD 284) onwards, barbarians settled and integrated into the Roman world.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Such settlers would have been granted certain legal rights simply by being within Roman territory, becoming *provinciales* and thus being eligible to serve as *auxilia* (auxiliary soldiers), which in turn made them eligible to become full *cives Romani*.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Through this relatively rapid process, thousands of former barbarians could quickly become Romans.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] This tradition of straightforward integration eventually culminated in the Antonine Constitution, issued by Emperor Caracalla in 212, in which all free inhabitants of Empire were granted the citizenship.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Caracalla's grant contributed to a vast increase in the number of people with the *nomen* (name indicating familial association) *Aurelius*.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] By the time of the Antonine Constitution, many people throughout the provinces already considered themselves (and were considered by others) as Romans.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Through the centuries of Roman expansion, large numbers of veterans and opportunists had settled in the provinces and colonies founded by Julius Caesar and Augustus alone saw between 500,000 and a million people from Italy settled in Rome's provinces.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In AD 14, four to seven percent of the free people in the provinces of the empire were already Roman citizens.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In addition to colonists, many provincials had also become citizens through grants by emperors and through other methods.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In most cases, it is not clear to what extent the majority of the new Roman citizens regarded themselves as being Roman, or to what extent they were regarded as such by others.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] For some provincials under Roman rule, the only experience with "Romans" prior to themselves being granted citizenship was through Rome's at times coercive tax-collection system or its army, aspects which were not assimilative in terms of forming an empire-spanning collective identity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Caracalla's grant marked a radical change in imperial policy towards the provincials.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] According to the British jurist Tony Honoré, the grant "gave many millions, perhaps a majority of the empire's inhabitants [...] a new consciousness of being Roman".
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Although there was a more or less unifying Roman identity, Roman culture in classical times was also far from homogeneous.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] There was a common cultural idiom, large portions of which was based in earlier Hellenistic culture, but Rome's strength also laid in its flexibility and its ability to incorporate traditions from other cultures.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] For instance, the religions of many conquered peoples were embraced through amalgamations of the gods of foreign pantheons with those of the Roman pantheon.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In Egypt, Roman emperors were seen as the successors of the pharaohs (in modern historiography termed the Roman pharaohs) and were depicted as such in artwork and in temples.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Many cults from the eastern Mediterranean and beyond spread to Western Europe over the course of Roman rule.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Once the very core of ancient Romanness, the city of Rome gradually lost its exceptional status within the empire in late antiquity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] By the end of the third century, the city's importance was almost entirely ideological, and several emperors and usurpers had begun reigning from other cities closer to the imperial frontier.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Rome's loss of status was also reflected in the perceptions of the city by the Roman populace.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In the writings of the 4th-century Greek-speaking Roman soldier and author Ammianus Marcellinus, Rome is described almost like a foreign city, with disparaging comments on its corruption and impurity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Few Romans in late antiquity embodied all aspects of traditional Romanness.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Many of them would have come from remote or less prestigious provinces and practiced religions and cults unheard of in Rome itself.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Many of them would also have spoken 'barbarian languages' or Greek instead of Latin.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Few inscriptions from late antiquity explicitly identify individuals as 'Roman citizens' or 'Romans'.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Before the Antonine Constitution, being a Roman had been a mark of distinction and often stressed, but after the 3rd century Roman status went without saying.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The prevalent view of the Romans themselves was that the *populus Romanus*, or Roman people, were a "people by constitution", as opposed to the barbarian peoples who were *gentes*, "peoples by descent" (i. e. ethnicities).
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Given that Romanness had become near-universal within the empire, local identities became more and more prominent.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In the late Roman Empire, one could identify as a Roman as a citizen of the empire, as a person originating from one of the major regions (Africa, Britannia, Gaul, Hispania etc.) or as originating from a specific province or city.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Though the Romans themselves did not see them as equivalent concepts, there is no fundamental difference between such Roman sub-identities and the *gens* identities ascribed to barbarians.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In some cases, Roman authors ascribed different qualities to citizens of different parts of the empire, such as Ammianus Marcellinus who wrote of the differences between 'Gauls' and 'Italians'.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In the late Roman army, there were regiments named after Roman sub-identities, such as 'Celts' and 'Batavians', as well as regiments named after barbarian *gentes*, such as the Franks or Saxons.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The Roman army underwent considerable changes in the 4th century, experiencing what some have called 'barbarisation', traditionally understood as the result of recruitments of large amounts of barbarian soldiers.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Though barbarian origins were seldom forgotten, the large scale and meritocratic nature of the Roman army made it relatively easy for "barbarian" recruits to enter the army and rise through the ranks only through their skills and achievements.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The rise of non-Roman customs in the Roman military might not have resulted from increasing numbers of barbarian recruits, but rather from Roman military units along the imperial borders forming their own distinctive identities.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] In the late empire, the term "barbarian" was sometimes used in a general sense by Romans not in the military for Roman soldiers stationed alongside the imperial border, in reference to their perceived aggressive nature.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] No matter the reason, the Roman military increasingly came to embody 'barbarian' aspects that in previous times had been considered antithetical to the Roman ideal.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Such aspects included emphasising strength and thirst for battle, as well as the assumption of "barbarian" strategies and customs, such as the *barritus* (a formerly Germanic battle cry), the *Schilderhebung* (raising an elected emperor up on a shield) as well as Germanic battle formations.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The assumption of these customs might instead of barbarisation be attributable to the Roman army simply adopting customs it found useful, a common practice.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Some barbarian soldiers recruited into the Roman army proudly embraced Roman identification and in some cases, the barbarian heritage of certain late Roman individuals was even completely ignored in the wider Roman world.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Religion had always been an important marker of Romanness.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] As Christianity gradually became the dominant religion in the Roman Empire through late antiquity, and eventually became the only legal faith, the Christianised Roman aristocracy had to redefine their Roman identity in Christian terms.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The rise of Christianity did not go unnoticed or unchallenged by the conservative elements of the pagan Roman elite, who became aware that power was slipping from their hands.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Many of them, pressured by the increasingly anti-pagan and militant Christians, turned to emphasising that they were the only 'true Romans' as they preserved the traditional Roman religion and literary culture.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] According to the Roman statesman and orator Quintus Aurelius Symmachus (c.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] 345–402), true Romans were those who followed the traditional Roman way of life, including its ancient religions, and it was adherence to those religions that in the end would protect the empire from its enemies, as in previous centuries.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Per Symmachus and his supporters, Romanness had nothing to do with Christianity, but depended on Rome's pagan past and its status as the heart of a vast and polytheistic empire.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The ideas of Symmachus were not popular among the Christians.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Some church leaders, such as Ambrose, the Archbishop of Mediolanum, launched formal and vicious assaults on paganism and those members of the elite which defended it.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Like Symmachus, Ambrose saw Rome as the greatest city of the Roman Empire, but not because of its pagan past but because of its Christian present.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Throughout late antiquity, Romanness became increasingly defined by Christian faith, which would eventually become the standard.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The status of Christianity was much increased through the adoption of the religion by the Roman emperors.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Throughout late antiquity, the emperors and their courts were viewed as the Romans *par excellence*.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] As the Roman Empire lost, or ceded control of, territories to various barbarian rulers, the status of the Roman citizens in those provinces sometimes came into question.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] People born as Roman citizens in regions that then came under barbarian control could be subjected to the same prejudice as barbarians were.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] Over the course of the Roman Empire, men from nearly all of its provinces had come to rule as emperors.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] As such, Roman identity remained political, rather than ethnic, and open to people of various origins.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] This nature of Roman identity ensured that there was never a strong consolidation of a 'core identity' of Romans in Italy, but also likely contributed to the long-term endurance and success of the Roman state.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p01] The fall of the Western Roman Empire coincided with the first time the Romans actively excluded an influential foreign group within the empire, the barbarian and barbarian-descended generals of the 5th century, from Roman identity and access to the Roman imperial throne.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The Roman Empire's expansion facilitated the spread of Roman identity over a large stretch of territories that had never before had a common identity and never would again.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The effects of Roman rule on the personal identities of the empire's subjects was considerable and the resulting Roman identity outlasted actual imperial control by several centuries.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] From the collapse of the Western Roman Empire in the late 5th century to the wars of Emperor Justinian I in the 6th century, the predominant structure of societies in the west was a near-completely barbarian military but also a near-completely Roman civil administration and aristocracy.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The new Barbarian rulers took steps to present themselves as legitimate rulers within the Roman framework, with the pretense of legitimacy being especially strong among the rulers of Italy.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The early kings of Italy, first Odoacer and then Theoderic the Great, were legally and ostensibly viceroys of the eastern emperor and thus integrated into the Roman government.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Like the western emperors before them, they continued to appoint western consuls, which were accepted in the east and by the other barbarian kings.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The imperial court in the east extended various honours to powerful barbarian rulers in the west, which was interpreted by the barbarians as enhancing their legitimacy; something they used to justify territorial expansion.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] In the early 6th century, Clovis I of the Franks and Theoderic the Great of the Ostrogoths nearly went to war with each other, a conflict that could have resulted in the re-establishment of the western empire under either king.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Concerned about such a prospect, the eastern court never again extended similar honours to western rulers, instead beginning to emphasise its own exclusive Roman legitimacy, which it would continue to do for the rest of its history.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Culturally and legally, Roman identity remained prominent in the west for centuries, still providing a sense of unity throughout the Mediterranean.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Italy's Ostrogothic Kingdom preserved the Roman Senate, which often dominated politics in Rome, illustrating the survival of and continued respect for Roman institutions and identity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The barbarian kings continued to use Roman law throughout the early Middle Ages, often issuing their own law collections.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Even after Italy was conquered by the Lombards in the late 6th century, the continued administration and urbanisation of northern Italy attest to a continued survival of Roman institutions and values.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Despite this, Roman identity was in a steep decline by the 7th and 8th centuries.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The great turning point in the history of the latter-day Romans of the west was the wars of Justinian I (533–555), aimed at reconquering the lost provinces of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] During Justinian's early reign, eastern authors re-wrote 5th-century history to portray the west as "lost" to barbarian invasions, rather than attempting to further integrate the barbarian rulers into the Roman world.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] As a result, Roman identity in the still barbarian-ruled regions (i.e.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Gaul, Spain and Britain) declined dramatically.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] During the reconquest of Italy, the Roman Senate disappeared and most of its members moved to Constantinople.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Though the senate achieved a certain legacy in the west, the end of the institution removed a group that had always set the standard of what Romanness was supposed to mean.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The war in Italy also divided the Roman elite there between those who enjoyed barbarian rule and those who supported the empire and later withdrew to imperial territory, meaning that Roman identity ceased to provide a sense of social and political cohesion.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The division of Western Europe into multiple different kingdoms accelerated the disappearance of Roman identity, as the previously unifying identity was replaced by local identities based on the region one was from.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The fading connectivitiy also meant that while largely Roman law and culture continued on, the language became increasingly fragmented and split, Latin gradually developing into what would become the modern Romance languages.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Where they had once been the majority of the population, the Romans of Gaul and Hispania gradually and quietly faded away as their descendants adopted other names and identities.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] In Sub-Roman Britain, the people of the large urban centers clung to Roman identity, but rural populations integrated and assimilated with Germanic colonisers (the Jutes, Angles and Saxons).
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Once the large cities declined, Roman identity faded away in Britain as well.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] In Hispania, "Gothic" transitioned from simply an ethnic identity to being both an ethnic one (in the sense of descent from Goths) and a political one (in the sense of allegiance to the king).
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Gothic becoming more fluid and multi-dimensional as an identity facilitated a smooth transition from people identifying as Romans to people identifying as Goths.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] There were few differences between the Goths and the Romans of Hispania at this point; the Visigoths no longer practised Arian Christianity and Romans, just like the Goths, were from the 6th century onwards allowed to serve in the military.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Though Roman identity was rapidly disappearing, the Visigothic Kingdom in the 6th and 7th centuries thus also produced several prominent latter-day Roman generals, such as Claudius and Paulus.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The disappearance of the Romans is reflected in the barbarian law collections.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] In the Salic law of Clovis I (from around 500), the Romans and the Franks are the two major parallel populations of the kingdom and both have well-defined legal statuses.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] A century later in the *Lex Ripuaria*, the Romans are just one of many smaller semi-free populations, restricted in their legal capacity, with many of their former advantages now associated with Frankish identity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Such legal arrangements would have been unthinkable under the Roman Empire and under the early decades of barbarian rule.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] By Charlemagne's imperial coronation in 800, Roman identity largely disappeared in Western Europe and fell to low social status.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Through suppressing Roman identity in the lands they ruled and discounting the remaining empire in the east as "Greek", the Frankish state hoped to avoid the possibility of the Roman people proclaiming a Roman emperor in the same way that the Franks proclaimed a Frankish king.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The population of the city of Rome continued to identify, and be identified, as Romans by westerners.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Although Rome's history was not forgotten, the city's importance in the Middle Ages primarily stemmed from it being the seat of the pope, a view shared by both westerners and the eastern empire.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] During the centuries following Justinian's reconquest, when the city was still under imperial control, the population was not specially administered and did not have any political participation in wider imperial affairs.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] When clashing with the emperors, the popes sometimes employed the fact that they had the backing of the *populus Romanus* ("people of Rome") as a legitimising factor, meaning that the city still endured some ideological importance in terms of Romanness.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Western European authors and intellectuals increasingly associated Romanness only with the city itself.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] By the second half of the 8th century, westerners almost exclusively used the term to refer to the population of the city.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] When the temporal power of the papacy was established through the foundation of the Papal States in the 8th century, the popes used the fact that they were accompanied and supported by the *populus Romanus* as something that legitimised their sovereignty.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The Roman populace considered neither the eastern empire nor Charlemagne's new "Holy Roman Empire" to be properly Roman.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Though the continuity from Rome to Constantinople was accepted in the west, surviving sources point to the easterners being seen as Greeks who had abandoned Rome and Roman identity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The Carolingian kings on the other hand were seen as having more to do with the Lombard kings of Italy than the ancient Roman emperors.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The medieval Romans also often equated the Franks with the ancient Gauls, and viewed them as aggressive, insolent and vain.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Despite this, the Holy Roman emperors were recognised by the citizens of Rome as true Roman emperors, albeit only because of their support and coronation by the popes.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The Franks and other westerners did not view the population of Rome favourably either.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Foreign sources are generally hostile, ascribing traits such as unrest and deceit to the Romans and describing them as "as proud as they are helpless".
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Anti-Roman sentiment lasted throughout the Middle Ages.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The Romans partly owed their bad reputation to sometimes trying to take an independent position towards the popes of the Holy Roman emperors.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Given that these rulers were seen as having universal power, the Romans were considered intruders in affairs that exceeded their competence.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Unlike the other kingdoms, the Vandal Kingdom in North Africa did not maintain a pretense of loyalty to the Roman Empire.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Since the term 'Roman' was seen as implying political loyalty to the empire, it was regarded by the Vandal government as politically loaded and suspicious.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] As a consequence, the Roman population of the kingdom rarely self-identified as such, though important markers of Romanness, such as Roman naming customs, adherence to Nicene Christianity as well as the Latin-language literary tradition, survived throughout the kingdom's existence.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Despite objections to 'Roman' as a term for the populace, the Vandals partly appealed to Roman legitimacy to legitimise themselves as rulers, given that the Vandal kings had marriage connections to the imperial Theodosian dynasty.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] However, the Vandal state more strongly worked to legitimise itself through appealing to the pre-Roman cultural elements of the region, particularly the Carthaginian Empire.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Some symbols of the ancient state were revived and the city of Carthage, capital of the kingdom, was heavily emphasised in poetry, on coinage and in the creation of a new "Carthaginian calendar".
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Coins minted by the Vandals were inscribed with *Felix Karthago* ("fortunate Carthage") and *Carthagine Perpetua* ("Carthage eternal").
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The Vandalic promotion of independent African symbols had a profound effect on the formerly Roman populace of their kingdom.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] By the time the soldiers of the eastern empire landed in Africa during Justinian's Vandalic War, the Romance people of North Africa had ceased to identify as Romans, instead preferring either Libyans (*Libicus*) or Punic people (*Punicus*).
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Contemporary eastern authors also described them as Libyans (Λίβυες).
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] During the Vandal Kingdom's brief existence, the Vandal ruling class had culturally and ethnically merged with the Romano-Africans.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] By the time the kingdom fell, the only real cultural differences between the "Libyans" and "Vandals" were that Vandals adhered to Arian Christianity and were permitted to serve in the army.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] After North Africa was reincorporated into the empire, the eastern Roman government deported the Vandals from the region, which shortly thereafter led to disappearance of the Vandals as a distinct group.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The only individuals recorded to have been deported were soldiers; given that the wives and children of the "Vandals" thus remained in North Africa, the name at this stage appears to mainly have denoted the soldier class.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Despite North Africa's reincorporation into the empire, the distinction between "Libyans" and "Romans" (i.e. the inhabitants of the eastern empire) was maintained by both groups.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Per the writings of the 6th-century eastern historian Procopius, the Libyans were descended from Romans, ruled by the Romans, and served in the Roman army, but their Romanness had diverged too much from that of the populace of the empire as a result of the century of Vandal rule.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Imperial policy reflected the view that the North Africans were no longer Romans.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Whereas governors in the eastern provinces were often native to their respective provinces, the military and administrative staff in North Africa was almost entirely constituted by easterners.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The distinction between the Romans and the Romance people of North Africa is also reflected in foreign sources, and the two populations appear to not yet have been reconciled by the time the African provinces fell during the Muslim conquest of the Maghreb and Roman rule was terminated.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] In the centuries when the Byzantine Empire was still a vast Mediterranean-spanning state, Roman identity was more strong in the imperial heartlands than on the peripheries, though it was also strongly embraced in the peripheral regions in times of uncertainty.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] As in earlier centuries, the Romans of the early Byzantine Empire were considered a people united by being subjects of the Roman state, rather than a people united through sharing ethnic descent (i.e.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] *gens* like those ascribed to different barbarian groups).
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The term extended to all Christian citizens of the empire, in a general sense referring to those who followed Chalcedonian Christianity and were loyal to the emperor.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] In Byzantine writings up until at least the 12th century, the idea of the Roman "homeland" consistently referred not to Greece or Italy, but to the entire old Roman world.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Despite this, the Romans of Byzantium were also aware that their present empire was no longer as powerful as it once had been, and that centuries of warfare and strife had left the Roman Empire reduced in territory and somewhat humbled.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] To the early Byzantines themselves, up until the 11th century or so, terms such as "Hellenes" were seen as offensive, as it downplayed their Roman nature and furthermore associated them with the ancient Pagan Greeks rather than the more recent Christian Romans.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The westerners were not unaware of Byzantium's Romanness; when not wishing to distance themselves from the eastern empire, the term *Romani* was frequently used for soldiers and subjects of the eastern emperors.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] From the 6th to 8th century, western authors also sometimes employed terms such as *res publica* or *sancta res publica* for the Byzantine Empire, still identifying it with the old Roman Republic.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Such references ceased as Byzantine control of Italy and Rome itself crumbled and the Papacy began to use the term for their own, much more regional, domain and sphere of influence.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] As the Byzantine Empire lost its territories in Egypt, the Levant and Italy, the Christians who lived in those regions ceased to be recognised by the Byzantine government as Romans, much in the same vein as had happened with the North Africans under Vandal rule.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The decrease in the diversity of peoples recognised as being Roman meant that the term Roman increasingly came to be applied only to the now dominant Hellenic population of the remaining territories, rather than to all imperial citizens.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] As the Hellenic populace were united by following Orthodox Christianity, spoke the same Greek language, and believed that they shared a common ethnic origin, "Roman" (*Rhōmaîoi* in Greek) thus gradually transformed into an ethnic identity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] By the late 7th century, Greek, rather than Latin, had begun being referred to in the east as the *rhomaisti* (Roman way of speaking).
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] At this point, "Roman" also began being used for Greek populations outside of the imperial borders, such as to the Greek-speaking Christians under Seljuk rule in Anatolia, who were referred to as *Rhōmaîoi* despite actively resisting attempts at re-integration by the Byzantine emperors.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Only a handful of late sources retain the old view of a Roman being a citizen of the Roman world.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The capture of Constantinople by the non-Roman Latin crusaders of the Fourth Crusade in 1204 ended the unbroken Roman continuity from Rome to Constantinople.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] In order to legitimise themselve as Romans in the decades when they no longer controlled Constantinople, the Byzantine elite began to look to other markers of what Romans were.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The elites of the Empire of Nicaea, the Byzantine government-in-exile, chiefly looked to Greek cultural heritage and Orthodox Christianity, connecting the contemporary Romans to the ancient Greeks.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] This contributed to Romanness becoming even more increasingly associated with people who were ethno-culturally Hellenic.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] 1254–1258), these ideas were taken further than ever before as they explicitly stated that the present *Rhōmaîoi* were *Hellenes*, descendants of the Ancient Greeks.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Though they saw themselves as Hellenic, the Nicene emperors also maintained that they were the only true Roman emperors.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] "Roman" and "Hellenic" were not viewed as opposing terms, but building blocks of the same double-identity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] During the rule of the Palaiologos dynasty, from the recapture of Constantinople in 1261 to the fall of the empire in 1453, *Hellene* lost ground as a self-identity, with few known uses of the term, and *Rhōmaîoi* once again became the dominant term used for self-description.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Some Byzantine authors went as far as to return to using "Hellenic" and "Greek" solely as terms for the ancient pagan Greeks.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] In the early modern period, many Ottoman Turks, especially those who lived in the cities and were not part of the military or administration, also self-identified as Romans (*Rūmī*, رومى), as inhabitants of former Byzantine territory.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The term *Rūmī* had originally been used by Muslims for Christians in general, though later became restricted to just the Byzantines.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] After 1453, the term was not only sometimes a Turkish self-identification, but it was also used to refer to Ottoman Turks by other Islamic states and peoples.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The identification of the Ottomans with the Romans was also made outside of the Islamic world.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] 16th-century Portuguese sources refer to the Ottomans they battled in the Indian Ocean as "rumes" and the Chinese Ming dynasty referred to the Ottomans as *Lumi* (魯迷), a transliteration of *Rūmī*, and to Constantinople as *Lumi cheng* (魯迷城, "Lumi city").
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] As applied to Ottoman Turks, *Rūmī* began to fall out of use at the end of the 17th century, and instead the word increasingly became associated only with the Greek population of the empire, a meaning that it still bears in Turkey today.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] As applied to the Greeks, the self-identity as Romans endured longer, and for a long time there was widespread hope that the Romans would be liberated and that their empire would be restored.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] By the time of the Greek War of Independence, the dominant self-identity of the Greeks was still *Rhōmaîoi* or *Romioi*.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The residents of Rome continue to identify with the demonym 'Roman' to this day.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Rome is the most populous city in Italy with the city proper being home to about 2.8 million citizens and the Rome metropolitan area to over four million people.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Since the collapse of the western Roman empire, the Papacy has continued the institution of the Pontifex Maximus and governments inspired by the ancient Roman Republic have been revived in the city four times.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Roman self-identification among Greeks remained throughout the Ottoman period.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The traveller and antiquary Richard Chandler, having travelled across Greece in the 1760s, remarked in 1776 that while the locals of Athens called the classical form of their language "Hellenic", they considered their present language and nation to be "Roman".
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Roman self-identification among Greeks only began losing ground with the Greek War of Independence, when multiple factors saw the name 'Hellene' rise to replace it.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Thus, in the eyes of the independence movement, a Hellene was a brave and rebellious freedom fighter while a Roman was an idle slave under the Ottomans.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The new Hellenic national identity was heavily focused on the cultural heritage of ancient Greece rather than medieval Byzantium, though adherence to Orthodox Christianity remained an important aspect of Greek identity.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] An identity re-oriented towards ancient Greece also worked in Greece's favour internationally.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] In Western Europe, the Greek War of Independence saw large-scale support owing to philhellenism, a sense of "civilisational debt" to the world of classical antiquity, rather than any actual interest in the modern country.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Despite the modern Greeks bearing more resemblance to the medieval Byzantines than the Greeks of the ancient world, public interest in the revolt elsewhere in Europe hinged almost entirely on sentimental and intellectual attachments to a romanticised version of ancient Greece.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Comparable uprisings against the Ottomans by other peoples in the Balkans, such as the First Serbian Uprising (1804–1814), had been almost entirely ignored in Western Europe.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Many Greeks, particularly those outside the then newly founded Greek state, continued to refer to themselves as *Romioi* well into the 20th century.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] What Greek identity ought to be remained unresolved for a long time.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] The modern Greek people still sometimes use *Romioi* to refer to themselves, as well as the term "Romaic" ("Roman") to refer to their Modern Greek language.
[src:boules/ancient-romans-p02] Roman identity also survives prominently in some of the Greek populations outside of Greece itself.
